INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('504', '1', '2013-11-04 09:47:05', '2013-11-04 09:47:05', '<strong>Attorney Bowen: </strong>My name is Brent Bowen. I am in Denton, Texas.  I have been practicing criminal law pretty much exclusively since 2003.\r\n\r\n<strong>Interviewer:</strong> What areas do you handle, just Denton or other cities or counties around there?\r\n\r\n<strong>Attorney Bowen: </strong>Denton County encompasses several cities. The cities of Denton, Lewisville, Hiram town, Briscoe are the big cities and there are several small cities close by, Highland Village, Argyle, and Sanger.\r\n\r\nI do practice in Tarrant County, which is Forth Worth, occasionally, and I also practice in Collin County, which is Plano, Frisco, McKinney, and occasionally will go to Wise Country, which is in Decatur.\r\n\r\n<b>Attorney Bowen Has Extensive Experience Defending DWI Cases </b>\r\n\r\n<strong>Interviewer: </strong>Today\'s subject will be about DWI. In the past 10 years how many cases do you think you have handled in that area?\r\n\r\n<strong>Attorney Bowen: </strong>It would be in the hundreds. It would be hard to estimate. I would say at least 400 to 500 DWI cases.\r\n\r\n<b>Is a Certain Demographic of Our Population Prone to DWI Charges?</b>\r\n\r\n<strong>Interviewer: </strong>Is there a typical person that ends up getting charged with DWI?\r\n\r\n<b>Any Driver Can Be Subject to a DWI Charge </b>\r\n\r\n<strong>Attorney Bowen: </strong>I would say that\'s the funny thing about DWI; there is no specific type of person. It can occur to anyone from a homeless man on the corner who happened to get the keys to a car to a CEO of a major company. Black or white, it doesn\'t really matter. DWI is one of those crimes that it can be a white collar or a blue collar crime. You just do not know. Anyone can get one.', 'Attorney Bowen Has Been Practicing Since 2003 and Works out of the Denton Area', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'attorney-bowen-has-been-practicing-since-2003-and-works-out-of-the-denton-area', '', '', '2013-11-05 06:49:36', '2013-11-05 06:49:36', '', '0', 'http://www.brentbowen.com/?page_id=504', '0', 'page', '', '0');
INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('505', '1', '2013-11-04 09:46:49', '2013-11-04 09:46:49', '<strong>Attorney Bowen: </strong>My name is Brent Bowen. I am in Denton, Texas.  I have been practicing criminal law pretty much exclusively since 2003.\r\n\r\n<strong>Interviewer:</strong> What areas do you handle, just Denton or other cities or counties around there?\r\n\r\n<strong>Attorney Bowen: </strong>Denton County encompasses several cities. The cities of Denton, Lewisville, Hiram town, Briscoe are the big cities and there are several small cities close by, Highland Village, Argyle, and Sanger.\r\n\r\nI do practice in Tarrant County, which is Forth Worth, occasionally, and I also practice in Collin County, which is Plano, Frisco, McKinney, and occasionally will go to Wise Country, which is in Decatur.\r\n\r\n<b>Attorney Bowen Has Extensive Experience Defending DWI Cases </b>\r\n\r\n<strong>Interviewer: </strong>Today\'s subject will be about DWI. In the past 10 years how many cases do you think you have handled in that area?\r\n\r\n<strong>Attorney Bowen: </strong>It would be in the hundreds. It would be hard to estimate. I would say at least 400 to 500 DWI cases.\r\n\r\n<b>Is a Certain Demographic of Our Population Prone to DWI Charges?</b>\r\n\r\n<strong>Interviewer: </strong>Is there a typical person that ends up getting charged with DWI?\r\n\r\n<b>Any Driver Can Be Subject to a DWI Charge </b>\r\n\r\n<strong>Attorney Bowen: </strong>I would say that\'s the funny thing about DWI; there is no specific type of person. It can occur to anyone from a homeless man on the corner who happened to get the keys to a car to a CEO of a major company. Black or white, it doesn\'t really matter. DWI is one of those crimes that it can be a white collar or a blue collar crime. You just do not know. Anyone can get one.', 'Attorney Bowen Has Been Practicing Since 2003 and Works out of the Denton Area', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '504-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-04 09:46:49', '2013-11-04 09:46:49', '', '504', 'http://www.brentbowen.com/504-revision-v1/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('506', '1', '2013-11-04 09:48:33', '2013-11-04 09:48:33', '<strong>Interviewer: </strong>When you see new clients, is there a typical back story on how they received the charges?\r\n\r\n<b>DWIs Are Prevalent in Close Proximity to Areas with as Large Concentration of Bars and at Major Sporting Events</b>\r\n\r\n<strong>Attorney Bowen: </strong>Typically, yes. Because we are here in Denton County we have the Texas Motor Speedway and occasionally when the races are here we will get DWIs from that event.\r\n\r\nThere are a couple of different bar districts in the county. One is over next to University of North Texas. At the University they have what is called Fry Street and so we obviously see a lot of DWIs occurring Fry Street. There are a couple of clubs down in Lewisville and restaurants up in Frisco, and so you will see DWIs from those areas as well.\r\n\r\n<b>Do Some People Feel This Charge Does Not Warrant Retaining an Attorney? </b>\r\n\r\n<strong>Interviewer:</strong> When this happens to someone, what is their typical reaction? Do they immediately call an attorney or do they think they do not need one?\r\n\r\n<b>Individuals That Received a DWI Have 15 Days in Which to Request a Hearing about Their Driver’s License at Motor Vehicles</b>\r\n\r\n<strong>Attorney Bowen: </strong>A lot of my clients, they end up playing around on the computer and so they see that they only have 15 days to request a hearing on their driver\'s license. We have University of North Texas as well as Texas Women\'s University, so we have two big colleges here in Denton.\r\n\r\n<b>Attorney Bowen Advices That Clients Should See an Attorney 3 to 5 Days following a DWI Charge</b>\r\n\r\nFrequently, if someone\'s son or daughter gets arrested for DWI, mom and dad are on the phone pretty quick trying to find an attorney. I try to get clients in my office within at least 3-5 days of them being arrested for DWI.', 'Is There a Typical Scenario When a Driver Is Arrested for DWI?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'is-there-a-typical-scenario-when-a-driver-is-arrested-for-dwi', '', '', '2013-11-05 06:50:19', '2013-11-05 06:50:19', '', '0', 'http://www.brentbowen.com/?page_id=506', '0', 'page', '', '0');
INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('507', '1', '2013-11-04 09:48:33', '2013-11-04 09:48:33', '<strong>Interviewer: </strong>When you see new clients, is there a typical back story on how they received the charges?\r\n\r\n<b>DWIs Are Prevalent in Close Proximity to Areas with as Large Concentration of Bars and at Major Sporting Events</b>\r\n\r\n<strong>Attorney Bowen: </strong>Typically, yes. Because we are here in Denton County we have the Texas Motor Speedway and occasionally when the races are here we will get DWIs from that event.\r\n\r\nThere are a couple of different bar districts in the county. One is over next to University of North Texas. At the University they have what is called Fry Street and so we obviously see a lot of DWIs occurring Fry Street. There are a couple of clubs down in Lewisville and restaurants up in Frisco, and so you will see DWIs from those areas as well.\r\n\r\n<b>Do Some People Feel This Charge Does Not Warrant Retaining an Attorney? </b>\r\n\r\n<strong>Interviewer:</strong> When this happens to someone, what is their typical reaction? Do they immediately call an attorney or do they think they do not need one?\r\n\r\n<b>Individuals That Received a DWI Have 15 Days in Which to Request a Hearing about Their Driver’s License at Motor Vehicles</b>\r\n\r\n<strong>Attorney Bowen: </strong>A lot of my clients, they end up playing around on the computer and so they see that they only have 15 days to request a hearing on their driver\'s license. We have University of North Texas as well as Texas Women\'s University, so we have two big colleges here in Denton.\r\n\r\n<b>Attorney Bowen Advices That Clients Should See an Attorney 3 to 5 Days following a DWI Charge</b>\r\n\r\nFrequently, if someone\'s son or daughter gets arrested for DWI, mom and dad are on the phone pretty quick trying to find an attorney. I try to get clients in my office within at least 3-5 days of them being arrested for DWI.', 'Is There a Typical Scenario When a Driver Is Arrested for DWI?', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '506-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-04 09:48:33', '2013-11-04 09:48:33', '', '506', 'http://www.brentbowen.com/506-revision-v1/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('508', '1', '2013-11-04 09:50:14', '2013-11-04 09:50:14', '<strong>Interviewer: </strong>As soon as someone is arrested, they are already on a short fuse. You said they have 15 days to contest losing their driver\'s license?\r\n\r\n<b>If You Do Not Request the ALR Hearing within 15 Days, Your License Will Be Suspended 40 Days from the Date of the DWI Arrest</b>\r\n\r\n<strong>Attorney Bowen:</strong> Yes. In Texas you have 15 days to request a driver\'s license hearing or Administrative License Revocation hearing or ALR for short. If you do not request that within the first 15 days then your driver\'s license will be suspended 40 days from the date of the arrest.\r\n\r\nIf you do not do anything, your license is suspended in 40 days from the date of the arrest. If we request a driver\'s license hearing that is the only due process hearing to challenge the facts behind the DWI and challenge the license suspension. Sometimes that hearing may be in 40 days or it may be 60 days from the date of the arrest. It is hard to tell sometimes.\r\n\r\n<b>Do People Tend to Disregard Requesting the Hearing?</b>\r\n\r\n<strong>Interviewer:</strong> Do you find that people actually just disregard the hearing because they feel their license will be suspended no matter what they do?\r\n\r\n<b>In Texas, a DWI Has Two Parts, a Civil and a Criminal</b>\r\n\r\n<strong>Attorney Bowen: </strong>They obviously do. The driver\'s license is technically civil so I tell people there are two parts to a DWI case, there is the civil driver\'s license part and then there is the criminal DWI. By statute they are separate and independent of one another.\r\n\r\n<b>Attorney Bowen Finds the Police Officer’s Testimony at the ALR Hearing a Valuable Resource for the Criminal Trial</b>\r\n\r\nI also explain, though, to my clients that the ALR is very important. Some people say, \"Oh, my license is going to get suspended anyway.\" I subpoena the officers for those driver\'s license hearings, and that is very important because we can then use the officer\'s testimonies, lock them down as you will, for trial.\r\n\r\nI have won countless jury trials because of how we locked down the officer at the ALR meeting, or at least use his testimony from the ALR hearing against him in trial.\r\n\r\n<strong>Interviewer: </strong>So the hearing is important whether you win it or not because you are getting a peek at what\'s ahead and what the prosecution will say happened and how to defend your client?\r\n\r\n<strong>Attorney Bowen:</strong> Correct. The officers typically, are not as prepared for the ALR hearings sometimes as they should be, and they have not been prepped, as you would, by the District Attorney\'s office and so they come in and they just testify to what they remember and that can be very helpful later on.', 'Requesting the Administrative License Revocation (ALR) Hearing', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'requesting-the-administrative-license-revocation-alr-hearing', '', '', '2013-11-05 06:50:21', '2013-11-05 06:50:21', '', '0', 'http://www.brentbowen.com/?page_id=508', '0', 'page', '', '0');
