INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('580', '1', '2013-11-25 06:31:59', '2013-11-25 06:31:59', '<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>Our firm is Bowen Law Group and I\'m Chrysandra Bowen.  I handle primarily family law.  Our law firm does cover criminal law also and as well as probate law.  We generally don’t work with large estates but we do handle some small estates.\r\n\r\nI tend to concentrate my area of practice on any matters dealing inside the family code for Texas and on the issues regarding children.  I do take care of CPS cases.  If children have been removed, I am court appointed and qualified to handle those cases.\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>What areas in the Dallas Fort Worth area do you cover?\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>We cover primarily Denton County.  That\'s where our office is based out of and then we handle cases in Weiss County, some in Cook County, a few in Collin County, and then occasionally we will travel to Fort Worth.  We cover all the cities that are in Denton County or within Denton County\'s region, which is somewhat large and kind of far.\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>Today\'s topic, we’ll do a review of family law and let\'s start off with divorce.\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>In Texas, you can get a divorce for grounds or no grounds.  Primarily the statute and legislature lays out presumption for a no fault divorce. No fault means that neither party is at fault and you just no longer have a supportable marriage. However, inside of pleading, you can plead for other issues and allegations that could have caused the breakdown of that marriage. Those allegations may support claims if you are seeking more than your 50% share of property and assets.\r\n\r\n<b>Divorces in Texas Cannot Be Finalized for at Least 60 Days from the Date of the Original Filing </b>\r\n\r\nWhen you are filing for divorce, you file a petition and that has to sit on file with the court for 60 days.  Most people misunderstand that.  They think that divorces are only supposed to be pending for 60 days. In that assumption, most people are referencing the timeframe from the date that you file with the court to a date that a final order or disposition of the case can be put into effect or signed by the court.\r\n\r\nThere has to be a 60 day lapse between that first date of filing and the 60 days to sign a final order or close the case out for the court system.  It doesn\'t have a bearing on your actual time frame, for example, your divorce can actually take longer, it could take less, it just depends on how you come into the office, whether it\'s an agreement, or if it is a contested case.\r\n\r\n<b>Men and Women Initiate an Equal Amount of Divorce Proceedings </b>\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>Do you get more men or women coming in for divorce?\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>I have about 50% for each that come in and are asking for advice on divorces and child custody.  There tends to be about the same equal division for child custody issues too.  Divorce doesn\'t always follow with child custody because sometimes the parents were never married or they are looking for some modification of a divorce where they were divorced prior and then the custody agreement is no longer working.  It\'s about 50/50 for both men and women.\r\n\r\nI know the rights and duties for both sides.  I know the preferences of the courts generally and that\'s partly why I try to concentrate more on practicing in the Denton County courts versus traveling all over in the area. This way, I can understand and keep up with the rules of the courts and their preferences of each of the judges that are in our area.', 'Texas Is a No Fault Divorce State', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'texas-is-a-no-fault-divorce-state', '', '', '2013-11-25 07:01:51', '2013-11-25 07:01:51', '', '0', 'http://www.brentbowen.com/?page_id=580', '0', 'page', '', '0');
INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('581', '1', '2013-11-25 06:31:59', '2013-11-25 06:31:59', '<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>Our firm is Bowen Law Group and I\'m Chrysandra Bowen.  I handle primarily family law.  Our law firm does cover criminal law also and as well as probate law.  We generally don’t work with large estates but we do handle some small estates.\r\n\r\nI tend to concentrate my area of practice on any matters dealing inside the family code for Texas and on the issues regarding children.  I do take care of CPS cases.  If children have been removed, I am court appointed and qualified to handle those cases.\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>What areas in the Dallas Fort Worth area do you cover?\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>We cover primarily Denton County.  That\'s where our office is based out of and then we handle cases in Weiss County, some in Cook County, a few in Collin County, and then occasionally we will travel to Fort Worth.  We cover all the cities that are in Denton County or within Denton County\'s region, which is somewhat large and kind of far.\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>Today\'s topic, we’ll do a review of family law and let\'s start off with divorce.\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>In Texas, you can get a divorce for grounds or no grounds.  Primarily the statute and legislature lays out presumption for a no fault divorce. No fault means that neither party is at fault and you just no longer have a supportable marriage. However, inside of pleading, you can plead for other issues and allegations that could have caused the breakdown of that marriage. Those allegations may support claims if you are seeking more than your 50% share of property and assets.\r\n\r\n<b>Divorces in Texas Cannot Be Finalized for at Least 60 Days from the Date of the Original Filing </b>\r\n\r\nWhen you are filing for divorce, you file a petition and that has to sit on file with the court for 60 days.  Most people misunderstand that.  They think that divorces are only supposed to be pending for 60 days. In that assumption, most people are referencing the timeframe from the date that you file with the court to a date that a final order or disposition of the case can be put into effect or signed by the court.\r\n\r\nThere has to be a 60 day lapse between that first date of filing and the 60 days to sign a final order or close the case out for the court system.  It doesn\'t have a bearing on your actual time frame, for example, your divorce can actually take longer, it could take less, it just depends on how you come into the office, whether it\'s an agreement, or if it is a contested case.\r\n\r\n<b>Men and Women Initiate an Equal Amount of Divorce Proceedings </b>\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>Do you get more men or women coming in for divorce?\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>I have about 50% for each that come in and are asking for advice on divorces and child custody.  There tends to be about the same equal division for child custody issues too.  Divorce doesn\'t always follow with child custody because sometimes the parents were never married or they are looking for some modification of a divorce where they were divorced prior and then the custody agreement is no longer working.  It\'s about 50/50 for both men and women.\r\n\r\nI know the rights and duties for both sides.  I know the preferences of the courts generally and that\'s partly why I try to concentrate more on practicing in the Denton County courts versus traveling all over in the area. This way, I can understand and keep up with the rules of the courts and their preferences of each of the judges that are in our area.', 'Texas Is a No Fault Divorce State', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '580-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-25 06:31:59', '2013-11-25 06:31:59', '', '580', 'http://www.brentbowen.com/580-revision-v1/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('582', '1', '2013-11-25 06:34:10', '2013-11-25 06:34:10', '<b>Interviewer: </b>How do child custody agreements work?  How do you explain that to someone that is coming in?\r\n\r\n<b>To Initiate a Child Custody Suit, Your Attorney Will File a Petition Asking the Court to Grant Custody</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>If you come into the office and you are asking or if your concern is that you\'ve either been served with a suit regarding your child relationship or a modification of those two regarding parent/child relationship, you do not have to follow the 60-day timeframe you do in a divorce.\r\n\r\nYou can file a petition and ask for custody, set out possession and rights, you can set out visitation, child support.  All of that is covered by a suit effecting parent/child relationship.  That can be filed by the mother or the father.\r\n\r\n<b>A Standing Order Is Attached to the Petition, Which Stipulates That the Current Custodial Parent Maintains the Status Quo or Care of the Children </b>\r\n\r\nGenerally here in Denton, every petition has a standing order attached to it.  All the judges have signed off on it.  It\'s an order that stipulates that you have to keep status quo regarding your children or your property.\r\n\r\n<b>Commonly, a Court Date Is Set and Negotiations May Begin with the Other Party’s Attorney Either Arranging or Prohibiting Visitation </b>\r\n\r\nWhat I would do is go through that standing order and explain what you can and can\'t do, also that once a child custody case is filed or you are responding to one, the process generally is we would set a court date or a court date has already been set. Additionally, we would start negotiation process with the other side, that way to ensure that each parent is getting some type of visitation or access or if they should not be getting visitation or access.\r\n\r\nWe would want to make sure that that was brought to the court\'s attention right away and we try to avoid jumping into a restraining order. The restraining order would have special circumstances and affidavits would be need to be signed and allegations would need to be made and presented to the court on those issues in order to keep the child from the other parent.\r\n\r\n<b>Child Custody Matters and Child Support Payment Matters Are Not Related to Each Other in Texas Courts </b>\r\n\r\nA large number of clients believe when they come to see me that custody and child support are related to each other. They feel justified in keeping the children away from the other parent if they are not getting child support.\r\n\r\n<b>The Courts Disapprove When One Parent Prohibits the Other’s Access to Children Based on Lack of Financial Support</b>\r\n\r\nThe case law is very firm and the courts tend to look down on it if you are keeping a child from a parent for not paying support.  There are avenues to get that money from the other parent that don\'t involve keeping a child from the parent as long as they are safe and stable.\r\n\r\n<b>Family Law Attorneys Also Handle Adoption Cases</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b> I see that you handle adoption.  How do you assist with that?\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>Adoptions are actually my favorite cases to handle.  I think that at the end of the day most everyone is very happy and it\'s also enjoyable for the court; it\'s fun for the family, it\'s a proceeding that is uplifting for everybody.  Now, adoptions can happen three ways.\r\n\r\n<b>An Adoption Can Be Initiated in Three Ways </b>\r\n\r\nIt can be that the parents have terminated rights previously and we are just filing an adoption.  There is an infant adoption where both parents are relinquishing their rights and asking for another couple to then take over conservatorship and adopt their child.\r\n\r\nThere is stepparent adoption, which means that one of the parents still has custody, either you are seeking termination of the rights of the other parent or they\'ve relinquished their rights and then the stepparent then would adopt the child and we would move forward that way.\r\n\r\n<b>The State of Texas Requires Criteria to Be Met Prior to an Adoption Being Finalized </b>\r\n\r\nThere are several components to an adoption that are state required.  You have to have home studies.  Those can cost anywhere from $700 to $2000 depending on the degree that you need.  Infant adoptions need two home study portions done versus a stepparent adoption, which only needs one portion.\r\n\r\nThere is some change in the case law that is coming up as far as adoptions and requirements for termination and adoption so that would be something that I will be following in keeping up with as the law changes.\r\n\r\n<b>In Adoptions, the Adoptee Is Required to Have Resided with the Future Parents for a Six Month Period</b>\r\n\r\nAt that point, you need relinquishments, waivers, medical history of the parent, and then it\'s a six month requirement that the child has to have lived with you for six months at some point.  The same thing goes for marriage.  You have to have been married so a stepparent can\'t get married and then immediately file for and ask for an adoption and they can plead an adoption.  They would actually have to wait for the six month requirement.\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>You mentioned child support modification, so is that a situation where one parent comes in and says that they want to modify what the amount is, either the party that is receiving the support or the party that is paying the support?\r\n\r\n<b>Texas Legislation Has Approved a Succession of Automatic Child Support Increases</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>We do see both parties come into the office.   Right now, the legislature passed a succession of increases that are automatic for child support.  There is a limit on what you can get as far as income that can be considered in Texas and over the next seven years that will increase.  That number is going to go up with inflation so someone that is already at limit, would obviously want to keep close contact with their attorney because then they can actually ask for more money or more child support at that point.\r\n\r\n<b>If Child Support Payments Have Not Been Modified in Several Years, a Modification Would Be Due but There Are Times When Child Support Is Decreased Rather than Increased </b>\r\n\r\nIf in three years the order hasn\'t been changed, you are entitled to come in and ask for a modification in child support.  Typically, it is increases versus decreasing but then in this economy that we\'ve had in the last three years, there has been several people that have lost their jobs, have gone on unemployment, have lost their unemployment, or have had to take lower paying jobs because they\'ve been laid off and just aren\'t able to keep up with the child support payment that they were originally making.\r\n\r\nThis is because they are not, by any fault necessarily of their own, no longer employed at the rate that they were and so aren\'t able to continue to make that payment.\r\n\r\nThe thing about Texas is that they will tack interest on whenever a payment is not made; there are other states that do not impose this interest.  Texas has an automatic interest payment and so anytime those payments aren\'t made, there is interest going to be added to those payments.', 'What Is the First Step in a Child Custody Case?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'what-is-the-first-step-in-a-child-custody-case', '', '', '2013-11-25 07:02:50', '2013-11-25 07:02:50', '', '0', 'http://www.brentbowen.com/?page_id=582', '0', 'page', '', '0');
