INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('584', '1', '2013-11-25 06:35:37', '2013-11-25 06:35:37', '<b>Interviewer: </b>What if someone who has custody of the child wanted to relocate with the child?\r\n\r\n<b>Texas Courts Prefer Both Parents Have Access to the Children</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>Relocation is sometimes harder.  The going norm in Texas is that to promote a relationship between the mom and the dad and the children and to have access to them, the judges tend to order the children reside in a set geographical location.\r\n\r\nThat\'s the common order here in Denton County actually is ensure the children reside anywhere within the Metroplex area or in the county that is touching our county.  That\'s pretty common throughout the Metroplex.  That\'s because the courts feel it is important to promote a relationship with both parents and the children.\r\n\r\nNow, in the last few years, again because of economy, many people have had to move to go wherever their job is or where the money is in order to continue to support themselves or to support their families and to make payments.\r\n\r\nMost often, you have inside a prior decree or a prior order, a clause that stipulates that you have to give a 60-day notice when you want to relocate.\r\n\r\n<b>If a Custodial Parents Wishes to Relocate, Their Attorney Must File a Motion to Modify in Order to Relocate </b>\r\n\r\nDepending on what the restrictions are or if you even have a restriction, you would have to file a motion to modify in order to be able to relocate.  You have to have specific reasons and it has to be in the best interest of the family.\r\n\r\nA number of parties get into trouble because they don\'t realize that they need to file a modification suit to relocate and they think they have agreements from the other party that they can move and then, low and behold, the other party has now filed an enforcement and the judge can make you move back. The judge can also take custody from you, and they can make you pay all the costs for the children to get back and forth for visitations.\r\n\r\n<b>Texas Courts Impose Penalties on the Parent That Moves Prior to or without Filing the Modification Motion</b>\r\n\r\nThere are some serious ramifications if you don\'t file to relocate and you just go ahead and move on your own.  The judges tend to take that more serious than I think most people realize that it would be.', 'Post-Divorce Relocation: What Is the Responsibility of the Custodial Parent?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'post-divorce-relocation-what-is-the-responsibility-of-the-custodial-parent', '', '', '2013-11-25 07:00:51', '2013-11-25 07:00:51', '', '0', 'http://www.brentbowen.com/?page_id=584', '0', 'page', '', '0');
