INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('586', '1', '2013-11-25 06:37:13', '2013-11-25 06:37:13', '<b>Interviewer: </b>Do domestic violence cases fall under family law?\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>It depends on what you are asking for.  The family code does allow for attorneys to follow for protective orders.   They don\'t have the same heat as a criminal case but they have the same aspect if a party was to violate a protective order or even it was done civilly versus through the district attorney\'s office.\r\n\r\n<b>The Family Law Attorney Can File for a Protective Order on Behalf of the Client</b>\r\n\r\nThis is because there are different burdens of proof for a protective order or for a civil law versus a protective order for criminal law, which we are allowed to do under the family code.  We can file and present both an exparte and a full blown final protective order.\r\n\r\nThere are time requirements, of course, because anything that is done without the other party\'s knowledge, they have to have, by law, notice of it and a chance to speak before anything permanent goes into effect.  Those generally last 14 to 20 days depending if you\'ve got a restraining order or if you\'ve got a protective order, or which one you are asking for if you are asking for an exparte.\r\n\r\nThen you have a hearing where the other party has been served and is present and is able to present evidence at that point to say yes, the allegations are true or no, the allegations are not true and those are all based off of affidavits, so, the same way that a criminal protective order would be obtained also applies to an exparte protective order.\r\n\r\n<b>A Final Protective Order Is Ordered for a Term of 2 Years; In Some Circumstances a Lifetime Order Can Be Requested </b>\r\n\r\nYou can ask for them for your children in your home if you have an ex that is hurting you or your children and you are remarried and then you have stepchildren, you ask for protection of anyone that is living in your home at that point through the civil protective order also.\r\n\r\nA final protective order lasts for two years but under certain circumstances you can actually ask for a longer term or a lifetime protective order now.  That is something that can be requested both criminally and civilly.\r\n\r\n<b>Is There a Difference between a Restraining and a Protective Order? </b>\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>What\'s the difference between a restraining order and a protective order?\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>A restraining order is that they are put on notice that they shouldn\'t be doing certain actions, the person is to refrain from doing them.  If a restraining order is violated, they are not arrested.  If they are violating a protective order, if they come near you, they come near the school, they take the children, they harass you then the person is looking at jail time.  They are automatically going to be arrested by the police and charged with a violation of protective order and taken to jail and then criminal charges will be filed.\r\n\r\n<b>Violations of a Restraining Usually Do Not Result in Arrest; Violations of a Protective Order Result in Arrest and Criminal Charges </b>\r\n\r\nWith a restraining order, it depends on the particular police department that gets called out.  It also depends upon what they are actually doing.  A restraining order can ask for someone to not be within the some distance from the other person or come to places or harass them.\r\n\r\nThat is primarily what a restraining order is. The purpose is to keep someone from harassing you but the ramifications of a restraining order are not the same as a protective order, which result in an automatic arrest.\r\n\r\n<b>What Actions Justify the Issuance of a Restraining Order? </b>\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>Does there necessarily have to be violence involved in order to get a restraining order?\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>Violence is not necessarily for a restraining order.  A protective order, yes, absolutely.  You need to show violence, as opposed to a restraining order which is issued just to prevent contact. It\'s not just domestic violence that needs to occur; it could be sexual abuse of a child or inappropriate touching or inappropriate punishment.  That can all fall underneath domestic violence.  Child abuse falls under protective orders also.\r\n\r\n<b>A Threat of Violence Warrants a Restraining Order</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>What if someone feels that there hasn\'t necessarily been violence occurring, what if it\'s just the threat of violence?\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>Yes, for example, if you are receiving a hundred text messages a day that range from I love you to I hate you, I want to kill you, those types of threats, absolutely you can get a restraining order.\r\n\r\nWhat I would advise is that you need to come in with those text messages, we will attach them, and if you are fearful that something is going to happen not only to you but possibly also your property, that is where your restraining order comes into place.', 'Do Domestic Violence Cases Fall under Family Law? ', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'do-domestic-violence-cases-fall-under-family-law', '', '', '2013-11-25 06:56:02', '2013-11-25 06:56:02', '', '0', 'http://www.brentbowen.com/?page_id=586', '0', 'page', '', '0');
