me at that point through the civil protective order also.\r\n\r\nA final protective order lasts for two years but under certain circumstances you can actually ask for a longer term or a lifetime protective order now.  That is something that can be requested both criminally and civilly.\r\n\r\n<b>Is There a Difference between a Restraining and a Protective Order? </b>\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>What\'s the difference between a restraining order and a protective order?\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>A restraining order is that they are put on notice that they shouldn\'t be doing certain actions, the person is to refrain from doing them.  If a restraining order is violated, they are not arrested.  If they are violating a protective order, if they come near you, they come near the school, they take the children, they harass you then the person is looking at jail time.  They are automatically going to be arrested by the police and charged with a violation of protective order and taken to jail and then criminal charges will be filed.\r\n\r\n<b>Violations of a Restraining Usually Do Not Result in Arrest; Violations of a Protective Order Result in Arrest and Criminal Charges </b>\r\n\r\nWith a restraining order, it depends on the particular police department that gets called out.  It also depends upon what they are actually doing.  A restraining order can ask for someone to not be within the some distance from the other person or come to places or harass them.\r\n\r\nThat is primarily what a restraining order is. The purpose is to keep someone from harassing you but the ramifications of a restraining order are not the same as a protective order, which result in an automatic arrest.\r\n\r\n<b>What Actions Justify the Issuance of a Restraining Order? </b>\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>Does there necessarily have to be violence involved in order to get a restraining order?\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>Violence is not necessarily for a restraining order.  A protective order, yes, absolutely.  You need to show violence, as opposed to a restraining order which is issued just to prevent contact. It\'s not just domestic violence that needs to occur; it could be sexual abuse of a child or inappropriate touching or inappropriate punishment.  That can all fall underneath domestic violence.  Child abuse falls under protective orders also.\r\n\r\n<b>A Threat of Violence Warrants a Restraining Order</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>What if someone feels that there hasn\'t necessarily been violence occurring, what if it\'s just the threat of violence?\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>Yes, for example, if you are receiving a hundred text messages a day that range from I love you to I hate you, I want to kill you, those types of threats, absolutely you can get a restraining order.\r\n\r\nWhat I would advise is that you need to come in with those text messages, we will attach them, and if you are fearful that something is going to happen not only to you but possibly also your property, that is where your restraining order comes into place.', 'Do Domestic Violence Cases Fall under Family Law? ', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '586-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-25 06:37:13', '2013-11-25 06:37:13', '', '586', 'http://www.brentbowen.com/586-revision-v1/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('588', '1', '2013-11-25 06:39:14', '2013-11-25 06:39:14', '<b>Interviewer: </b>Could you tell us about family law mediation and what is its purpose?\r\n\r\n<b>Mediation Can Save Money and Lessen Emotional Stress</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>Mediation is a good tool for family law.  It is cost effective as long as the parties are reasonably in the same area or close to deciding on certain issues such as property distribution or child custody or child support.  As long as you are within the same range of each other or realm, mediation can be very effective for family law and it saves you the emotion and the trauma of going to court and the cost.\r\n\r\nIn mediation, generally the attorney and the party are in a room.  The other attorney and the other party are in another room, and a qualified mediator can be an attorney and a judge, someone who has been through the training to mediate.\r\n\r\nMost of the time, family law attorneys are looking for someone that practices in the area in front of the same judges so that way they can take that back to the room and use that as a basis for knowledge of what you could get in court or what you couldn\'t get in court.  Mediation is a balance of what the judge is ultimately probably going to decide based off of your facts and what you are wanting.\r\n\r\n<b>Parties Have More Control over Issues in Mediation than They Might in the Courtroom</b>\r\n\r\nIn mediation, you have control over the decision and how you are distributing your property and your custody and all of the issues dealing with your divorce or custody matter.  In trial, you are completely at the mercy of the judge and whatever the judge decides.  There are time limits in court.  It takes longer to get to court.\r\n\r\nYou are constrained by the rules of evidence for presenting items in court so you might have something but if you don\'t have the ability to present it or if it is statements made by the child, those are hearsay statements.  You can\'t get those into court but the particular item might be the meat of what your case is about or your concerns are about.\r\n\r\nMediation is important because you can actually talk about those things.  You can say this is where my stance is.  The other party can say this is where their stance is and the mediator will go back and forth and try to get you somewhere in the middle.\r\n\r\nMediation isn\'t necessarily a win for either party.  It\'s a getting you to a place where you are comfortable to say I want this done, I feel like I\'ve given and at the end of the day, we were able to keep control of how the outcome came to be versus a judge telling us how to be.\r\n\r\nYou have control over all of the small details can be addressed in mediation where sometimes in trial there is only time to address the big points and the big issues.', 'Family Law Mediation Process', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'family-law-mediation-process', '', '', '2013-11-25 07:58:12', '2013-11-25 07:58:12', '', '0', 'http://www.brentbowen.com/?page_id=588', '0', 'page', '', '0');
