t', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '592-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-25 06:41:46', '2013-11-25 06:41:46', '', '592', 'http://www.brentbowen.com/592-revision-v1/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('594', '1', '2013-11-25 06:43:41', '2013-11-25 06:43:41', '<b>Interviewer: </b>You mentioned CPS cases, how do you become involved with those cases?  What role do you play?\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>I have done both private and court appointed CPS cases.  In private cases, I represent the parents when CPS has come in and taken their children and removed them from their home and then they are ordered to do services throughout the year that is required.\r\n\r\n<b>A Family Law Attorney Can Be Retained Privately or Be Court Appointed If They Possess the Appropriate Training</b>\r\n\r\nI have been hired privately but I also meet the requirements and keep up with my education and training to be on the court appointed list, which when someone is indigent, they can apply for a court appointed attorney and the court appoints me to a parent or I am appointed to children.\r\n\r\nPrimarily, in court appointment, I am appointed to children probably 60% and to parents 40% and that\'s just the way that it tends to fall because there is a requirement that a child that is in CPS care is appointed an attorney.  There are more attorneys needed for children than there are for parents.\r\n\r\nThis is because not all the parents are actually qualified for a court appointed attorney, which is why I again, you sometimes need to seek out a private attorney and pay for them privately and I\'ve done some of those cases.\r\n\r\n<b>Parents Must Qualify for a Court Appointed Attorney in a CPS Case, Eligibility Is Based on Income Level</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>Why would they not be qualified for a court appointed attorney?\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>Because it is based on of your income and the size of your household.  You have to meet the poverty level threshold in order to qualify for a court appointed attorney.  It\'s not automatic.\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>So they have to fall underneath with the federal poverty income guidelines then, that\'s based on that household and total amount of children.\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>Yes.\r\n\r\n<b>An Attorney That Represents Both Children and Parents Has a Unique Perspective of a CPS Case</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>So you are saying that you are getting to see both perspectives in those cases?\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>Yes, I think is a benefit to work both sides, to work for the children and to work for the parent. Working for the children, you have a very close relationship working with both your advocates, your CASA appointed advocates and your CPS workers.\r\n\r\nYou develop relationships with them, which can benefit you in your cases where you are the parent\'s attorney because conflict in your case can be driven by the parent\'s ability to communicate and keep up with their service plan and their CPS worker.\r\n\r\n<b>It Is Important for the Attorney to Develop a Good Relationship with the CPS Caseworker </b>\r\n\r\nIf you have a good working relationship with your CPS worker and you are attentive to the case, that tends to help your case progress in a natural flow versus having to go to court all the time to ask for things, such as increased visits or if there is a concern for the child.\r\n\r\nIf you have a good working relationship with your advocates and your CPS workers, you are able to actually ask the district attorney and all of them to meet and have a conference versus we have to go to court multiple times to ask for these all of the time.\r\n\r\nIt also gives you a perspective on the viability of your case as far as what requirements that CPS is looking at, both for the parents and for the child to be returned home.  If you are always on one side, you can\'t see the whole perspective in presenting a case as to what is everybody looking at and what requirements do they want you to meet.\r\n\r\nUltimately at the end of the day if the district attorney is fighting for termination of a parent\'s right, as a parent\'s attorney, it\'s good to have a well-rounded view so that way you can see that this is what we need to do moving forward.\r\n\r\n<b>How Can a Parent Facilitate Being Reunited with Their Children? </b>\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>What are some ways you can help with the parents in that in getting the child back?  What are some options that they have?\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>I tend to have a real conversation about my clients about if a service plan, which will be instituted if we are not able to get the children back at the beginning. It is important for them to have a plan of action in place before temporary orders and the service plan are entered with the court, which that doesn\'t happen in every case.  Very rarely do you have a situation where a child shouldn\'t have qualified for an emergency removal.  There are cases where they do, they should be removed, and you can win them, it just doesn\'t happen very often here in Denton County.\r\n\r\n<b>Parents Need to Set and Meet Definable Goals in Order to Be Reunited with Their Children </b>\r\n\r\nAt that point, once a service plan has been put in place, I have a real conversation with my clients about their service plan. I explain this is where we need to go, these are our goals and this is how we need to be keeping track of everything and how we need to be communicating with CPS in order to move forward to get your children back without even going through a termination trial.\r\n\r\nWe do have success in these cases.  The goal is to get your children returned to your home well prior to the year requirement that the legislature has laid out for us to be in a child\'s life.\r\n\r\nGenerally, about the sixth month mark is where CPS is looking at whether or not they are going to change their goal to termination or reunification, depending on the status and services of the parents and how the parents have done. We want to be able to be at that sixth month mark and say we\'ve done what we need to do, we\'ve learned, and we\'re getting our children back at this point.\r\n\r\n<b>CPS Intervention Can Ultimately Be a Positive Experience for a Family </b>\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>Are parents generally cooperative at that point and how is their emotional mindset?\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>It depends on the parents.  CPS involvement can either be a really life changing thing that is positive for a parent or it can be something that parents really struggle and fight.  Again, it comes down to how you have to look at it.\r\n\r\nUltimate success depends on your ability to complete things that you have been given to complete.  As long as you have the right mind frame. Whether you believe that they should be in your life or they shouldn\'t be in your life, as long as you are doing the things that you are required to do by the court, that is who you ultimately have to answer to is the court, not CPS, it\'s to the court.\r\n\r\nNaturally, most parents actually are not receptive when children are initially removed from their home.  No one wants their children removed from them, good, bad, or indifferent.  So they are not receptive to CPS or the process but the idea is that at some point you have to get on the game plan and start working towards it because at the end of the day, the judge is the ultimately decision maker and he or she got the ability to say you can have your children back or you can\'t have your children back.\r\n\r\nIf they\'ve put that temporary order in place saying that you need to do these things to get your children back then parents have to understand that they are going to have to do those things and take those steps in order to get them back.', 'Can a Family Law Attorney Be Involved in Child Protective Services’ Cases? ', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'can-a-family-law-attorney-be-involved-in-child-protective-services-cases', '', '', '2013-11-25 06:54:10', '2013-11-25 06:54:10', '', '0', 'http://www.brentbowen.com/?page_id=594', '0', 'page', '', '0');
INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('595', '1', '2013-11-25 06:43:41', '2013-11-25 06:43:41', '<b>Interviewer: </b>You mentioned CPS cases, how do you become involved with those cases?  What role do you play?\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>I have done both private and court appointed CPS cases.  In private cases, I represent the parents when CPS has come in and taken their children and removed them from their home and then they are ordered to do services throughout the year that is required.\r\n\r\n<b>A Family Law Attorney Can Be Retained Privately or Be Court Appointed If They Possess the Appropriate Training</b>\r\n\r\nI have been hired privately but I also meet the requirements and keep up with my education and training to be on the court appointed list, which when someone is indigent, they can apply for a court appointed attorney and the court appoints me to a parent or I am appointed to children.\r\n\r\nPrimarily, in court appointment, I am appointed to children probably 60% and to parents 40% and that\'s just the way that it tends to fall because there is a requirement that a child that is in CPS care is appointed an attorney.  There are more attorneys needed for children than there are for parents.\r\n\r\nThis is because not all the parents are actually qualified for a court appointed attorney, which is why I again, you sometimes need to seek out a private attorney and pay for them privately and I\'ve done some of those cases.\r\n\r\n<b>Parents Must Qualify for a Court Appointed Attorney in a CPS Case, Eligibility Is Based on Income Level</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>Why would they not be qualified for a court appointed attorney?\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>Because it is based on of your income and the size of your household.  You have to meet the poverty level threshold in order to qualify for a court appointed attorney.  It\'s not automatic.\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>So they have to fall underneath with the federal poverty income guidelines then, that\'s based on that household and total amount of children.\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>Yes.\r\n\r\n<b>An Attorney That Represents Both Children and Parents Has a Unique Perspective of a CPS Case</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>So you are saying that you are getting to see both perspectives in those cases?\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>Yes, I think is a benefit to work both sides, to work for the children and to work for the parent. Working for the children, you have a very close relationship working with both your advocates, your CASA appointed advocates and your CPS workers.\r\n\r\nYou develop relationships with them, which can benefit you in your cases where you are the parent\'s attorney because conflict in your case can be driven by the parent\'s ability to communicate and keep up with their service plan and their CPS worker.\r\n\r\n<b>It Is Important for the Attorney to Develop a Good Relationship with the CPS Caseworker </b>\r\n\r\nIf you have a good working relationship with your CPS worker and you are attentive to the case, that tends to help your case progress in a natural flow versus having to go to court all the time to ask for things, such as increased visits or if there is a concern for the child.\r\n\r\nIf you have a good working relationship with your advocates and your CPS workers, you are able to actually ask the district attorney and all of them to meet and have a conference versus we have to go to court multiple times to ask for these all of the time.\r\n\r\nIt also gives you a perspective on the viability of your case as far as what requirements that CPS is looking at, both for the parents and for the child to be returned home.  If you are always on one side, you can\'t see the whole perspective in presenting a case as to what is everybody looking at and what requirements do they want you to meet.\r\n\r\nUltimately at the end of the day if the district attorney is fighting for termination of a parent\'s right, as a parent\'s attorney, it\'s good to have a well-rounded view so that way you can see that this is what we need to do moving forward.\r\n\r\n<b>How Can a Parent Facilitate Being Reunited with Their Children? </b>\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>What are some ways you can help with the parents in that in getting the child back?  What are some options that they have?\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>I tend to have a real conversation about my clients about if a service plan, which will be instituted if we are not able to get the children back at the beginning. It is important for them to have a plan of action in place before temporary orders and the service plan are entered with the court, which that doesn\'t happen in every case.  Very rarely do you have a situation where a child shouldn\'t have qualified for an emergency removal.  There are cases where they do, they should be removed, and you can win them, it just doesn\'t happen very often here in Denton County.\r\n\r\n<b>Parents Need to Set and Meet Definable Goals in Order to Be Reunited with Their Children </b>\r\n\r\nAt that point, once a service plan has been put in place, I have a real conversation with my clients about their service plan. I explain this is where we need to go, these are our goals and this is how we need to be keeping track of everything and how we need to be communicating with CPS in order to move forward to get your children back without even going through a termination trial.\r\n\r\nWe do have success in these cases.  The goal is to get your children returned to your home well prior to the year requirement that the legislature has laid out for us to be in a child\'s life.\r\n\r\nGenerally, about the sixth month mark is where CPS is looking at whether or not they are going to change their goal to termination or reunification, depending on the status and services of the parents and how the parents have done. We want to be able to be at that sixth month mark and say we\'ve done what we need to do, we\'ve learned, and we\'re getting our children back at this point.\r\n\r\n<b>CPS Intervention Can Ultimately Be a Positive Experience for a Family </b>\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>Are parents generally cooperative at that point and how is their emotional mindset?\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>It depends on the parents.  CPS involvement can either be a really life changing thing that is positive for a parent or it can be something that parents really struggle and fight.  Again, it comes down to how you have to look at it.\r\n\r\nUltimate success depends on your ability to complete things that you have been given to complete.  As long as you have the right mind frame. Whether you believe that they should be in your life or they shouldn\'t be in your life, as long as you are doing the things that you are required to do by the court, that is who you ultimately have to answer to is the court, not CPS, it\'s to the court.\r\n\r\nNaturally, most parents actually are not receptive when children are initially removed from their home.  No one wants their children removed from them, good, bad, or indifferent.  So they are not receptive to CPS or the process but the idea is that at some point you have to get on the game plan and start working towards it because at the end of the day, the judge is the ultimately decision maker and he or she got the ability to say you can have your children back or you can\'t have your children back.\r\n\r\nIf they\'ve put that temporary order in place saying that you need to do these things to get your children back then parents have to understand that they are going to have to do those things and take those steps in order to get them back.', 'Can a Family Law Attorney Be Involved in Child Protective Services’ Cases? ', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '594-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-11-25 06:43:41', '2013-11-25 06:43:41', '', '594', 'http://www.brentbowen.com/594-revision-v1/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('596', '1', '2013-11-25 06:45:17', '2013-11-25 06:45:17', '<b>Interviewer: </b>Does annulment ever come into conversation with some of the clients?\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>You know, I actually, I\'ve only had two people in the five and a half years I\'ve been practicing ask about it.  They didn\'t meet the requirements for it so I wouldn\'t say that that is a common thing.  More often or not, you do have people that come in that are common law married asking for an annulment and then it has to be determined whether or not they meet the requirements and classifications for a common law marriage.\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>What are the requirements for an annulment and what are the requirements of a common law marriage?\r\n\r\n<b>There Are Strict Criteria Regarding the Common Law Marriage Classification</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>With common law marriage, there are three requirements and you have to meet all three.  Essentially, the idea in common law marriage is that you\'ve been living in a married state, you have property, and you portray yourselves as husband and wife.  That\'s what a common law marriage is and there are strict requirements regarding the classification.\r\n\r\nThere is paperwork that you can file that say that you are common law married in order for insurance purposes or with the county for property. There are forms and affidavits that people can actually sign that say that makes your job easier to prove a common law marriage.\r\n\r\nIf you are common law married and you meet the requirements then you have to get a divorce in order to separate your property. There is also a presumption of law that if you haven\'t been living together, cohabitated, or portrayed yourselves as married or have common property in the last two years then it is as if you were never married anyway.\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>One of the things I hear about common law marriages is that if people thought that if they have been living with together for five years, does that mean they are married?\r\n\r\n<b>Couples That Only Live Together Are Not Classified as Being in a Common Law Marriage</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>Not necessarily.  Like I said, it depends on how you refer to each other.  For example, if you are holding yourselves out as husband and wife and if you have property together.  Many people do start saying, my husband or my wife the longer that you\'ve been together without being married.\r\n\r\nThe caveat is that you can never have intended to get married at a future date so it can\'t be that you got engaged three years ago and you just never got married.  It\'s not necessarily that.  The intention cannot ever be there that you are going to get married at the date, it\'s that you have been married the entire time, that this person has been my spouse the entire time, from the date we were saying we were husband and wife.\r\n\r\n<b>Family Law Case History </b>\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>Do you have a unique case that happened within the past five years that was memorable and pertains to family law?\r\n\r\n<b>A Family Law Attorney Handles Many Unique Cases</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>I\'ve actually been fortunate in having some really unique issues and cases just on a normal basis.  I would say that I enjoy my cases that come in that aren\'t your normal we need to separate property and we need to separate kids.\r\n\r\nI do work for the domestic violence shelter here in town.  They send cases over for people that have protective orders that need divorces.  I am on that list to help them and I understand domestic violence.  I\'m not a specialist by any means but I have handled a lot of domestic violence cases where there has been domestic violence between the parents or sexual abuse to the children.\r\n\r\n<b>The Most Memorable Cases May Involve Righting a Wrong  </b>\r\n\r\nI\'ve had several cases where one of the parents has been accused of molesting the child and ultimately at the end of the day able to prove that the child has not been molested.  Those are huge wins.\r\n\r\nThat type of case takes a lot of preparation and investigation and the parents really have to be willing to put themselves through the ringer in order to prove their innocence but I have been successful in that those are victories.  That\'s a huge win for both the parent and for me because you are righting a wrong at that point.  That makes your job worth it.\r\n\r\nI love adoption cases and being able to put a child into a home that is good and safe.\r\n\r\nI have handled many domestic violence cases too, where the wives experienced years of abuse. I have been able to put that on the record and put that out there on the stand and ask the questions.  It\'s always a questionable practice of whether or not to put a victim on the stand and how will they do that or the system victimizing them over again.\r\n\r\nYou will see that quite frequently in domestic violence cases where the other party will use the court system in order to victimize them more because your hands are tied if you can\'t get in front of the court.  There are only so many things you can do.\r\n\r\nAbusers tend to have control over finances and property and children.   I\'ve had cases where the abuser has come in and claimed or asked for a protective order or a restraining order and we\'ve had to come in and show that type of deception is a form of abuse also. I enjoy helping my clients receive help and counseling so they can have a better life.\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>We have talked about divorce, child custody, adoption, child support modification, child relocations, domestic violence, family law mediation, restraining orders, and CPS cases.  Out of all of those, which are the most difficult cases that you take on?', 'Common Law Marriage and Annulment', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'common-law-marriage-and-annulment', '', '', '2013-11-25 06:55:08', '2013-11-25 06:55:08', '', '0', 'http://www.brentbowen.com/?page_id=596', '0', 'page', '', '0');
