INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('635', '1', '2014-01-30 10:19:34', '2014-01-30 10:19:34', '<b>Interviewer: </b>We will be going over a review of the criminal law process.  Can you give us an overview of criminal defense?\r\n\r\n<b>Brent Bowen: </b>Criminal law is broken down two ways; adult criminal law, and then juvenile law.  It’s probably easiest to talk about juveniles first.  Juvenile law is civil in nature.  It’s kind of a hybrid criminal/civil.  There is typically no criminal conviction at the end.  You’re filed like a civil case, by a petition being filed in court.\r\n\r\n<strong>Juvenile Crimes Typically Do Not Entail a Criminal Conviction and the Juvenile Is Viewed as Being Detained, Not Incarcerated</strong>\r\n\r\nYou’re not arrested, you’re detained.  There’s no bond in a juvenile case, so we have to come back every two weeks for a detention hearing, to determine if the court’s going to release you, and if you’re a danger to yourself or the public, and if the child needs supervision.  Juvenile is criminal in terms of, there are crimes involved, but it’s done in a separate format in Texas.\r\n\r\n<strong>Adult Crime in Texas Is Divided into Misdemeanor or Felony Charges</strong>\r\n\r\nNext we have criminal law.  Crimes in Texas are divided up between misdemeanors or felonies.  Misdemeanors start with a Class-C, which would be the equivalent of a traffic ticket or a DUI, driving under the influence of alcohol or a minor in possession of alcohol.  Those are Class-C tickets, as well as speeding-type offenses and traffic offenses.\r\n\r\nNext we have Class-B misdemeanors.  Class-B misdemeanors typically carry with it a range of punishment of up to 180 days or six months in jail, and a $2,000 fine.  There is a Class-A misdemeanor, which is the highest misdemeanor, which is punishable up to a year in jail and a $4,000 fine.\r\n\r\nNext we have felonies.  We have a felony offense and a first offense is a state jail felony.  It’s kind of a hybrid misdemeanor/felony offense, meaning the punishment range is six months to two years in a state jail facility.  There is an optional fine not to exceed $10,000.\r\n\r\nThe next felony would be a third degree felony, which would be two to ten years in prison.  The next would be a second degree felony, which is two to twenty years in prison, then a first degree felony is five to 99 at present, and then we have obviously habitual offenses.\r\n\r\n<b>Texas Has a DUI and a DWI Charge; the DUI Charge Is Primarily for Minor Drivers under the Age of 21</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>You mentioned the DUI.  What is a DUI versus a DWI?\r\n\r\n<b>Brent Bowen: </b>In Texas, a DUI is driving under the influence and is a zero tolerance law. That means the charge will be leveled for any detectable amount of alcohol for minors.  If you have any alcohol in your system at all, as a minor under 21, then you’re DUI.  Whether you’re intoxicated or not, it’s just a DUI.\r\n\r\nA DWI is driving while intoxicated and is a class B misdemeanor; that is the intoxication standard where you talk about 0.08 or more. In Texas, intoxication is designated as 0.08 or more. This is classified as a loss of normal mental faculties or loss of normal physical faculties, due to alcohol or drugs in the system.\r\n\r\nA 20-year old, or under 21-year-old, could still be charged with DWI, which is the higher offense, but a lot of times they’re charged with a lower DUI offense.', 'In Texas, Criminal Law Is Separated into Adult Criminal Law and Juvenile Criminal Law', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'in-texas-criminal-law-is-separated-into-adult-criminal-law-and-juvenile-criminal-law', '', '', '2014-01-30 10:56:52', '2014-01-30 10:56:52', '', '0', 'http://www.brentbowen.com/?page_id=635', '0', 'page', '', '0');
