INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('637', '1', '2014-01-30 10:22:55', '2014-01-30 10:22:55', '<b>Interviewer: </b>Aside from DUI, DWI, what are some of the most common types of crimes that you represent people for?\r\n\r\n<b>Brent Bowen: </b>Unfortunately, in a college town, we get a lot of marijuana.  In Texas, marijuana’s still illegal.  With a large college population here in Denton, we do a lot of possession of marijuana cases.  We handle many drug cases in general, whether they are attributed to methamphetamine, cocaine and infrequently, heroin. Methamphetamine is the most common drug, aside from marijuana.\r\n\r\nThen next most common cases are assaults; assault-type cases, whether it’s a few men fighting or family members, such as between brother and sister or husband and wife.\r\n\r\n<b>White Collar Crimes Include Fraud and Forgery</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>  Are there any “white collar” crimes?\r\n\r\n<b>Brent Bowen: </b>Occasionally we have a fraud or a forgery cases.  A few years ago, the health department was cracking down on welfare fraud cases. If you received extra benefits based on not reporting some income on your food stamp obligation, then they were prosecuting you for fraud.  We do see a little bit of that.  They normally charge it as theft, though; that’s the easiest way to charge it.\r\n\r\n<b>Unlawful Possession of Identifying Information</b>\r\n\r\nThere’s also what’s called unlawful possession of identifying information, which is kind of white collar crime and is similar to identity theft. This is a crime where someone possesses another individual’s ID.  Those cases can get pretty tricky in my experience.\r\n\r\nI’ve had a few cases where the police have charged, say, a brother with using the other brother’s information, which is known as unlawfully possessing identifying information.\r\n\r\nMy problem there is, if I know my brother’s address and date of birth, and obviously his name, am I now a felon if I use it unlawfully, because I possessed it?   I have a twin brother, so that makes it really interesting, because I know a lot of information about my twin brother.  They have to prove that I unlawfully used it.  That kind of case can become fairly complicated.\r\n\r\n<strong>The Federal Government, as Opposed to the State Government, Usually Prosecutes Mortgage Fraud Cases</strong>\r\n\r\nWe don’t see a great number of white collar crimes.  Normally, the ones I’ve seen where it’s really a mortgage fraud type case, the federal government tends to pick those up.  We’ve had a couple here in Denton, but really what we see more of is the identity theft and the food stamp fraud.\r\n\r\n<b>Food Stamp Fraud Can Be Prosecuted as a Felony Charge</b>\r\n\r\nA lot of times the food stamp’s cases are just ridiculous.  They forgot to report that they made a couple of dollars here and there, and next thing they know they owe the government or the state hundreds of dollars, and they’re being prosecuted as felons because of it.\r\n\r\nI think the cases are more due to the poor paperwork management of the government than it is people intentionally not reporting income, although it probably goes a little bit both ways.\r\n\r\nProbably what it more billows down to is, let’s say I get laid off; or, I have a job, but because my job pays me so little, and I have so many kids, that I qualify for food stamps.  We put that down; then I am laid off.\r\n\r\nMaybe we get that last paycheck and somehow we didn’t report it. This was because I have now already applied for unemployment but I have not yet received unemployment checks. You report your income that month; the next month you report double the income, because you have received the unemployment check.  Because of that money, you become ineligible for food stamps.\r\n\r\nWe’ve got a lot of problems where someone might get maybe a disability check one month, and not get it the next month, or maybe it was reported one month, but because it got reported that month and maybe they didn’t get it that month. There are many different scenarios.  You may qualify for food stamps one month for some reason, and not the next, because of how much money that may have come in that month.\r\n\r\nIf you are receiving government assistance, it is important to remember to report all income.  Again, I think a lot of it is some people forget to report things.  Many times, the person reporting the information is not writing it down correctly.', 'Criminal Defense Includes Drug-Related Charges, Such as Possession of Marijuana ', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'criminal-defense-includes-drug-related-charges-such-as-possession-of-marijuana', '', '', '2014-01-30 10:56:16', '2014-01-30 10:56:16', '', '0', 'http://www.brentbowen.com/?page_id=637', '0', 'page', '', '0');
