INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('639', '1', '2014-01-30 10:24:43', '2014-01-30 10:24:43', '<b>Interviewer: </b>What are some of the common misconceptions people have about being arrested, or when they’re talking to you about criminal law?\r\n\r\n<b>Brent Bowen: </b>I know people are confused about the court date.  That’s the trial date.  People think, “Well, I’m set up for trial on my ticket, and if the officer doesn’t show, I will be acquitted.”  That doesn’t happen anymore, because typically you have a very specific court date for specific purposes.\r\n\r\n<b>It Is Advisable Not to Wait to Hire an Attorney</b>\r\n\r\nI think some people, especially lately, have been waiting to hire attorneys.  They think they don’t need to hire an attorney unless the case files.  Oftentimes, there are actions the attorney can do to keep the case from being filed, and that may be worth a lot more money to you than waiting until the case gets filed.\r\n\r\nLately, I’m getting calls from people that were arrested two or three months ago, but the case is just now going to court. Now, they’re scrambling trying to find an attorney.  In my opinion, it can be a mistake not to get an attorney involved early when they can do a full investigation. This is because they may be able to prevent charges from being filed in the first place.\r\n\r\n<strong>In the Denton County Area, an Individual Cannot Be Released from Jail until a Judge Reviews the Paperwork and Sets a Bond</strong>\r\n\r\nSometimes we get phone calls from people when their loved one is arrested.  Some counties are a little different, but in most counties in this area, there is really not much an attorney can do until the bond is set.\r\n\r\nThe judge comes in and reviews the paperwork and sets a bond.  When this happens depends on when the arrest was made. Normally at 2 o’clock in the morning, I’m not going to call a judge and wake him up to get a bond set.\r\n\r\n<strong>A Defense Attorney Must Wait until a Judge Has Set a Bond to Have His Client Released from Jail</strong>\r\n\r\nPersonally, I don’t mind answering questions at 2 o’clock in the morning, but at the same time, I’m probably not going to be able to get a loved one out of jail at that time.  Again, we have to wait for a judge to come in.\r\n\r\n<b>Why Is It Important to Retain an Attorney before a Case Is Filed?</b>\r\n\r\nIn Denton County, once someone’s arrested, it can take several weeks or maybe months for a case to actually be filed.  Some people think, “Well, it’s not filed immediately and I don’t have to worry about it.”  A couple months go by, and all of a sudden, valuable time that we could have been researching and working on the cases, have flown by.  We’re a little behind the ball trying to get papers and documents and evidence we need that we could have already reviewed—if we had been hired earlier in the process.\r\n\r\n<strong>DWI and DUI Charges Are Handled Differently; a Driver Must Request a Hearing to Avoid the License Suspension within 15 Days of the Arrest</strong>\r\n\r\nDWI’s are handled a little differently. With DWIs, we only have 15 days to request a hearing on a driver’s license if someone’s arrested.  That’s something we definitely try to emphasize, and emphasize on our Web site. If you are arrested for DWI, or even a DUI, you only have 15 days to request a hearing, or your license will automatically be suspended.  You won’t get your due process hearing.', 'Common Misconceptions after an Arrest', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'common-misconceptions-after-an-arrest', '', '', '2014-01-30 10:55:40', '2014-01-30 10:55:40', '', '0', 'http://www.brentbowen.com/?page_id=639', '0', 'page', '', '0');
