INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('641', '1', '2014-01-30 10:25:56', '2014-01-30 10:25:56', '<b>Interviewer: </b>What are some ways that people unintentionally incriminate themselves?  What are some of the mistakes that they make?\r\n\r\n<b>It Is Very Unlikely You Can Talk Your Way out of a Criminal Charge</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Brent Bowen: </b>Some people who are fairly intelligent think they can talk their way out of an offense.  That’s probably the biggest headache that we see. This is when people start talking and trying to talk their way out of it.  They say things that they wouldn’t ordinarily say that usually are incriminating.  Or, they just sound stupid; that’s going to make them look bad in front of a jury.\r\n\r\nMy advice is, other than answering the basic questions of your name and address is simply not to talk.  Just be quiet.  If this officer’s going to arrest you, he’s going to arrest you.  You’re not going to be able to talk your way out of it.  A number of people, they just keep talking and many times, they’re just digging that hole deeper and deeper and deeper.\r\n\r\nThat’s probably the biggest thing I see when I’m reviewing cases is, people just saying things they shouldn’t say, and just really incriminating themselves, or just looking bad in general.\r\n\r\n<b>When Should You Hear the Miranda Rights?</b>\r\n\r\nSome clients have come in lately saying, “They didn’t read me my Miranda rights, so the case should go away.”  You would be surprised at the number of people that think if the police didn’t read you Miranda, then there’s no case.\r\n\r\n<strong>Custodial Interrogation: The Miranda Rights Should Be Read after an Arrest and before You Are Being Interrogated</strong>\r\n\r\nMiranda only applies to a custodial interrogation, which means the police are not investigating anymore and you’re actually arrested.  If the investigation part is over or they’ve actually arrested you and put you in cuffs and if they interrogate you about the crime—that’s when Miranda applies.\r\n\r\nThey don’t have to read you Miranda when they first get you out of your car on DWI or a marijuana case.  If they ask you questions after you’re arrested, that could incriminate you, then those statements would be inadmissible in court if they did not read the Miranda rights.  They couldn’t use those against you—but—it doesn’t negate the actual case.', 'What to Avoid during and after an Arrest', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'what-to-avoid-during-and-after-an-arrest', '', '', '2014-01-30 10:54:57', '2014-01-30 10:54:57', '', '0', 'http://www.brentbowen.com/?page_id=641', '0', 'page', '', '0');
