da applies.\r\n\r\nThey don’t have to read you Miranda when they first get you out of your car on DWI or a marijuana case.  If they ask you questions after you’re arrested, that could incriminate you, then those statements would be inadmissible in court if they did not read the Miranda rights.  They couldn’t use those against you—but—it doesn’t negate the actual case.', 'What to Avoid during and after an Arrest', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '641-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-01-30 10:25:56', '2014-01-30 10:25:56', '', '641', 'http://www.brentbowen.com/641-revision-v1/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('643', '1', '2014-01-30 10:29:15', '2014-01-30 10:29:15', '<b>Interviewer: </b>Do you think police officers intentionally ask particular questions in order to get information about people or have them incriminate themselves?\r\n\r\n<b>Brent Bowen: </b>They absolutely do.  Police absolutely are now trained, in my opinion, to immediately ask you all sorts of incriminating questions when they first make contact with you.  At that point in time, there’s really no crime, in their opinion, that’s probably been committed.  You’re not under arrest, and there’s no way I can prove that you are under arrest.  They’re going to ask you all sorts of questions.\r\n\r\n<strong>Other than Providing Basic Information, You Do Not Have to Answer Police Questions</strong>\r\n\r\nPolice even get demanding at times about you answering their questions.  Again, you’re not under arrest.  You don’t have to answer their questions.  Other than providing your driver’s license and insurance if you get pulled over, you don’t have to say anything.\r\n\r\nFrequently, officers want to make small talk; “Where you going tonight?  Where you coming from?  You been drinking?  How many you had to drink?  What’s your address?  Where are you headed to?  Why don’t you know your friend’s address that you’re going to?”\r\n\r\n<b>You Do Not Have to Consent to a Search of Your Vehicle</b>\r\n\r\nThey may ask all sorts of questions.  Also, too, they’ll ask you for to consent to a search of your car, or search yourself; “Hey, can I search your car?”  People think if they say no, that that gives them a reason to actually search the car, and it does not.\r\n\r\nYou saying, “No, officer, I don’t want you searching my car,” doesn’t give them reason to search their car.  You would think that that would create a reason, but it does not.\r\n\r\n<strong>If You Are Pulled over, It Is Better to Ask Questions, Rather Than Answer Them</strong>\r\n\r\nI’ve always told clients, if they are pulled over and the officer wants to search, say, “Officer I’d love to, but I’ve got to run.  I’m in a huge hurry and you’re inconveniencing me at this time.  Can I leave?”\r\n\r\nThat’s the kind of question you have to ask an officer.  “Officer, am I free to go?”  If he says no, now you’ve defined the detention.  At that point forward, it’s a detention.  He has to be able to articulate why he’s detaining you, to further some sort of other investigation.\r\n\r\nI’d rather people ask questions, than answer questions, if that makes sense.\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>That does make sense.  I’ve always wondered why a police officer will begin sometimes, at a regular traffic stop, “Do you know how fast you were going?”  Is that an opener to incriminate someone right there, if they admit they were speeding?\r\n\r\n<b>Brent Bowen: </b>Yes, that’s exactly right.  They’re immediately asking to see if you know you’re driving fast.  You’ll say, “Oh yes, officer, I’m sorry.”  They’re trying to get that incriminating statement.  Or, “Hey, how come you’re driving so poorly tonight?”  That’s one of those questions, too, that you see in a lot of DWIs.\r\n\r\n“Was there something going on?  Is something wrong with your car, or are you just driving bad?  Why are you driving badly tonight?”  Now you’re inferring that you agree that you made if you answer that you know you’re driving skills appear poor.\r\n\r\nThere are many trick questions that officers want to ask, and they ask them up front because again, they know Miranda typically is not going to apply at that stage in the game.\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>I wouldn’t really know how to answer that.  What would be the best way to answer something like that?  Say I’m just driving to the store, and they say, “Why are you driving badly?”\r\n\r\n<b>Brent Bowen: </b>Just say, “I didn’t know I was.”\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>Do I have to provide them with a reason?\r\n\r\n<b>The Texting Defense Has Been Used Successfully to Combat a DWI Charge Attributed to Erratic Driving</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Brent Bowen: </b>No, that is not necessary.  Don’t say medications; that’ll get you a DWI, too, even though it’s not alcohol.  The best answer would be, “I was texting, I was on the phone,” something like that.  I’ve actually won DWI cases with the texting defense; it worked.\r\n\r\nThe officer claimed, “The driver was all over the road,” but then once he gets out of the car, he looks doesn’t appear intoxicated, but the officer still arrests him for DWI.  Why was he driving badly?  He’s texting.  Why does he look so good when he gets out of the car?  Because he’s not drunk; he was texting in the car.\r\n\r\n<b>Some Cities in Texas Are Beginning to Ban Texting While Driving</b>\r\n\r\nThis works as long as you’re in a jurisdiction that allows you to text.  Some city ordinances are banning texting while driving, or even using a hand-held cell phone while driving.  That’s kind of a new issue occurring city by city.  The state’s not going to do it.  I think they might eventually, but as of right now, the state hasn’t outlawed cell phones other than in school zones.  Cities are doing it themselves.\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>Corpus Christi has already adapted that one.\r\n\r\n<b>Brent Bowen: </b>That is the same as where the Cowboys play; there’s a no-handheld ban in Arlington, Texas.', 'Will the Police Word Questions to Elicit Incriminating Answers?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'will-the-police-word-questions-to-elicit-incriminating-answers', '', '', '2014-01-30 10:54:17', '2014-01-30 10:54:17', '', '0', 'http://www.brentbowen.com/?page_id=643', '0', 'page', '', '0');
