INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('645', '1', '2014-01-30 10:31:04', '2014-01-30 10:31:04', '<b>Interviewer: </b>What have you learned about people’s behavior, and their reaction to being arrested and prosecuted for a crime?  What sort of human insights have you gained into the whole process?\r\n\r\n<strong>It Is Natural to Try and Cooperate but It Is Best to Say as Little as Possible to the Police</strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Brent Bowen: </b>I think a lot of people, for the most part, want to cooperate.  They want to be helpful.  They want to tell the officer the truth.  The problem is the truth won’t set you free.  The truth will only incriminate you. I would, again, rather people just didn’t say anything at all, than try to be so truthful and helpful to the officers. This is because it definitely makes an attorney’s job much harder when that happens.\r\n\r\nBe polite, be respectful.  You’d love to do something for the officer, but you just can’t right now.  You’ve got to get somewhere; you’re in a hurry.  “Thank you, officer, but I’ve got to go.  Can I leave now?”  You’ve got to be somewhat forceful in wanting to leave, but still courteous and cooperative with the officer.\r\n\r\nIf it turns bad and you’re courteous and cooperative but somewhat demanding with the officer, and asking questions, that’s only going to help your defense.  The officer then has to legally justify why he’s continuing to detain you.  If he can’t do that, then that’s a huge benefit for you. It might go a long way toward having a case or a piece of evidence suppressed or dismissed.\r\n\r\n<b>Police Cars Are Equipped with Video Cameras</b>\r\n\r\nI think people forget that everything’s videotaped nowadays. It begins from when they pull you over, when they activate their lights and sirens the video cameras are on.  When you’re in the back of the police car, there’s a video camera on you.  If they have to manually turn the camera around, they will.  Some of them actually have two cameras, one facing forward and one facing rear, so they can get you in the back seat of the car.\r\n\r\n<b>Some Officers Wear Body Cameras</b>\r\n\r\nI think people need to remember that once they see an officer, they are on camera the whole time.  The new thing here and a few of our agencies now are body cameras, where they have little cameras on their shoulders or on their lapels.  The whole encounter, face-to-face, is also recorded.  If people see an officer, they better assume they’re on camera, and they’re being videotaped.  Don’t say anything or say very little.\r\n\r\n<strong>Do the Body Cameras Offer Better Benefits to the Police or the Person Involved in the Police Stop?</strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>Do the body cameras benefit the officers, or do they work better to protect someone’s rights?\r\n\r\n<b>Brent Bowen: </b>Everything a person does is recorded on the camera.  If someone looks suspicious or intoxicated, and the officer’s wearing the body camera and it’s picking up all their facial expressions that’s definitely going to be more helpful for police.\r\n\r\nI’ve seen a few cases over the years, where police turn their back, and their camera’s running on their patrol car, and the woman reaches down into her bustier and pulls something out, typically drugs and throws it away.  The officer never sees it; but it’s all caught on camera.\r\n\r\nI think cameras have only helped police.  Obviously, because there’s so much video, there’s been cases where police misconduct has been captured on video.  I would love to see more video from that standpoint.  Overall, I think video is both good and it’s bad for defendants.', 'Do People Experience Common Reactions after Being Arrested?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'do-people-experience-common-reactions-after-being-arrested', '', '', '2014-01-30 10:53:38', '2014-01-30 10:53:38', '', '0', 'http://www.brentbowen.com/?page_id=645', '0', 'page', '', '0');
