INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('649', '1', '2014-01-30 10:33:47', '2014-01-30 10:33:47', '<b>Interviewer: </b>How does someone know that they’re under criminal investigation and will be charged with a crime?\r\n\r\n<b>Brent Bowen: </b>Normally, the police will contact you and want to question you.  Oftentimes, the police will tell you, “You’re not under arrest, we just need to visit with you about your case, or about doing an investigation, and we should talk to you.”  People will go and talk with the police, and again, same premise about Miranda doesn’t apply.  You’re free to go.  The officer will tell you up front, “Hey, you’re free to go.  We just want to chat with you about this case or that; what’s going on, or we’re investigating this.”\r\n\r\n<strong>If You Are Contacted about a Case, It Is Advisable to Contact an Attorney before Speaking Further with the Police</strong>\r\n\r\nPeople do want to just go chat, and talk with the police, and give them information.  Obviously, number one, if you think you’re under investigation, the police will actually contact you to talk about the case.\r\n\r\nFrom there, most of the time people are smart.  They’ll get an attorney involved right then and there, or they’ll just go talk with the police.  Once you talk with the police, it’s permanent.  I can’t really change that.  You voluntarily went down to visit with the police and discuss your case.  I can’t change those facts, whatever information you gave them.\r\n\r\nThe police can lie to you, but you can’t lie to the police.  The courts have said that they can kind of bend the rules a little bit, or bend the truth, in order to try to get you to confess, but you cannot lie to the police.  You don’t have that same advantage. You can say nothing, but once you start lying, consequences will happen.\r\n\r\nIt’s important, if you think you’re going to be the target of an investigation, it’s very important to talk to an attorney and find out what’s going on.\r\n\r\nI can call an investigator, talk to him, and give him a story.  That’s not really giving them information, in terms of that they might, “A client said this or that.”  In my opinion, it is better to get an attorney involved.\r\n\r\n<strong>The Attorney Can Talk to the Police on Your Behalf and If Needed, Start Their Own Investigation about a Crime You Might Be Charged with</strong>\r\n\r\nLet them ask the questions.  Let them talk to the police.  Let them decide if, “Hey, this is something where I think we should talk to this person or not.” It may be that there’s not enough there.  Why even give them the time of day?  Or, there’s too much there, and you definitely don’t want to talk to them, because they’re just looking for the last nail in the coffin.\r\n\r\nIt’s really better to get an attorney involved.  I’ve had a case right now where a client was arrested for aggravated assault and a deadly weapon, because he had a knife on him.  We had done a little bit of investigation and determined that actually he had been the victim of an assault.  The police just, for some reason, didn’t like my client.\r\n\r\nWe actually had to go to the police department and demand that they investigate it fully and get a detective involved.  Once we demanded that, and we provided all the witness statements, the DA just declined to prosecute my client for the aggravated assault with a deadly weapon.\r\n\r\nHad he gone himself to try to do all that, they may have questioned him a little differently and tried to skew it more towards that he was guilty.  Because I was involved, I was able to control the way the interview went.  That helped show that really, he was the victim of a crime, not the perpetrator of a crime.', 'How Will You Know You Are the Subject of a Criminal Investigation?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'how-will-you-know-you-are-the-subject-of-a-criminal-investigation', '', '', '2014-01-30 10:52:33', '2014-01-30 10:52:33', '', '0', 'http://www.brentbowen.com/?page_id=649', '0', 'page', '', '0');
