INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('651', '1', '2014-01-30 10:34:48', '2014-01-30 10:34:48', '<b>Interviewer: </b>Are people obligated to meet with detectives?  How does one go about communicating with an officer?  How do they say, “I’d like to not answer your questions and get a lawyer” without getting them too upset with you?\r\n\r\n<strong>If You Contact an Attorney, He or She Can Communicate Further with the Police</strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Brent Bowen: </b>If I tell the officer, “I want to go talk to an attorney,” he’s going to think I’ve got something to hide.  No, you just want to explore your options.  Like you just said, “Do I have to talk to this police officer, or can I go and figure something out myself?  What are my rights?”  People think, “Well, if I go with them, they’ll have to read Miranda, and then I’ll invoke them.”  No, they don’t have to read Miranda if you’re free to go.\r\n\r\nYou’ve got to be careful in terms of the “kill them with kindness” approach.  “Officer, I would love to help you, but I just don’t have the time right now.” Or, “Honest, I’d love to help you, but I need to get some more information from you officers as to what you’re looking at, and how I might be a part of that.”\r\n\r\nAgain, it goes back to what I mentioned earlier, which is to ask the officer lots of questions.  Then say, “Officer, basically from what you’ve told me, I’d feel comfortable talking with an attorney first, and I’ll have him get in touch with you.”  I’ll call the officer back and say, “We’re not going to talk to you.”  Or, “When do you want to schedule time to talk?” based on what you’ve told me.\r\n\r\nI’ve dealt with a lot of these officers for a number of years, and so some of them are going to tell me, “It doesn’t matter if you talk to me or not, I’m getting a warrant.”  They’re honest.  They really can’t lie to me.  If they lie to me, that’s going to look bad, because that’s going to get brought up in court.  The jury’s not going to like that the officer’s lying to attorneys.\r\n\r\nJuries tend to be like, “Oh, we see, officer.  You’re trying to come to the truth by lying to the poor person who’s on trial.”  Again, I’ve had officers who say, “Honestly, I don’t know what happened.  This person’s story would help me determine if I’m going to do X, Y or Z.”\r\n\r\n<strong>In Any Interaction with the Police, It Is Always Advisable to be Courteous and Respectful</strong>\r\n\r\nI’ve represented officers in the past.  I am never rude to officers.  In court, in front of a jury, I may be a little bit tougher on an officer, but day-to-day I’ll get more information with officers by being nice to them and talking to them.\r\n\r\nBecause of that, I was just asked to speak last month at a police officer’s educational update for them.  They basically had free reign to ask me all sorts of questions for an hour and a half, and they did.  I kind of gave them the good and bad; what they do well and what they don’t do well and sometimes what I look for to make them look bad.  Because of that, they tend to be pretty up front with me, if I call an officer about one of my clients.', 'In What Way Should You Decline to Answer Police Questions?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'in-what-way-should-you-decline-to-answer-police-questions', '', '', '2014-01-30 10:52:04', '2014-01-30 10:52:04', '', '0', 'http://www.brentbowen.com/?page_id=651', '0', 'page', '', '0');
INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('652', '1', '2014-01-30 10:34:48', '2014-01-30 10:34:48', '<b>Interviewer: </b>Are people obligated to meet with detectives?  How does one go about communicating with an officer?  How do they say, “I’d like to not answer your questions and get a lawyer” without getting them too upset with you?\r\n\r\n<strong>If You Contact an Attorney, He or She Can Communicate Further with the Police</strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Brent Bowen: </b>If I tell the officer, “I want to go talk to an attorney,” he’s going to think I’ve got something to hide.  No, you just want to explore your options.  Like you just said, “Do I have to talk to this police officer, or can I go and figure something out myself?  What are my rights?”  People think, “Well, if I go with them, they’ll have to read Miranda, and then I’ll invoke them.”  No, they don’t have to read Miranda if you’re free to go.\r\n\r\nYou’ve got to be careful in terms of the “kill them with kindness” approach.  “Officer, I would love to help you, but I just don’t have the time right now.” Or, “Honest, I’d love to help you, but I need to get some more information from you officers as to what you’re looking at, and how I might be a part of that.”\r\n\r\nAgain, it goes back to what I mentioned earlier, which is to ask the officer lots of questions.  Then say, “Officer, basically from what you’ve told me, I’d feel comfortable talking with an attorney first, and I’ll have him get in touch with you.”  I’ll call the officer back and say, “We’re not going to talk to you.”  Or, “When do you want to schedule time to talk?” based on what you’ve told me.\r\n\r\nI’ve dealt with a lot of these officers for a number of years, and so some of them are going to tell me, “It doesn’t matter if you talk to me or not, I’m getting a warrant.”  They’re honest.  They really can’t lie to me.  If they lie to me, that’s going to look bad, because that’s going to get brought up in court.  The jury’s not going to like that the officer’s lying to attorneys.\r\n\r\nJuries tend to be like, “Oh, we see, officer.  You’re trying to come to the truth by lying to the poor person who’s on trial.”  Again, I’ve had officers who say, “Honestly, I don’t know what happened.  This person’s story would help me determine if I’m going to do X, Y or Z.”\r\n\r\n<strong>In Any Interaction with the Police, It Is Always Advisable to be Courteous and Respectful</strong>\r\n\r\nI’ve represented officers in the past.  I am never rude to officers.  In court, in front of a jury, I may be a little bit tougher on an officer, but day-to-day I’ll get more information with officers by being nice to them and talking to them.\r\n\r\nBecause of that, I was just asked to speak last month at a police officer’s educational update for them.  They basically had free reign to ask me all sorts of questions for an hour and a half, and they did.  I kind of gave them the good and bad; what they do well and what they don’t do well and sometimes what I look for to make them look bad.  Because of that, they tend to be pretty up front with me, if I call an officer about one of my clients.', 'In What Way Should You Decline to Answer Police Questions?', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '651-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-01-30 10:34:48', '2014-01-30 10:34:48', '', '651', 'http://www.brentbowen.com/651-revision-v1/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('653', '1', '2014-01-30 10:38:34', '2014-01-30 10:38:34', '<b>Interviewer: </b>For people who don’t know technical jargon, or legal jargon, what does it mean to be indicted?  How does bail work?  How is bail set?\r\n\r\n<b>Brent Bowen: </b>Let’s talk about the bail first, because that’s the first thing that’s going to happen.  Normally, in Texas when you are arrested, you’ll have to wait and see the judge or the magistrate.  They have to read you certain warnings and they’re going to set up bonds.  Sometimes there’s a set bond schedule.\r\n\r\n<strong>The Amount of Bond That Is Set Is Determined by the Severity of the Crime</strong>\r\n\r\nNormally, bond is set on the severity of the crime, and the criminal history; the likelihood to return to court.  Those are the main factors that a judge is looking for in setting bond.  If this is a really bad person, obviously we may not want him out to do any more crimes.  A first-time offender, never been in trouble before then we probably don’t have to worry about this individual and will set a lower bond.\r\n\r\nAlso taken into account is: Are they going to show up for court?  Are they from the area?  Do they have a lot of ties to the area?  Did their parents grow up here, and do they have a business here?\r\n\r\n<b>You Can Pay a Cash Bond or Hire a Bail Bondsman</b>\r\n\r\nThat’s the way bond’s set or there’s a set bond schedule, but that can still deviate based on those other factors.  Once bond’s set, you can always pay a cash bond.  A cash bond is where your family member brings the cash up to the jail, they write your receipt, and that cash insures that you’re going to show up for court.\r\n\r\nOr, you can hire a bail bondsman.  That bail bond is going to get a fee.  That’s their fee to ensure that you show up for court.  In Denton County, the going rate is like 10 percent, but maybe in Tarrant County, sometimes it’s 20 percent.  If you have an immigration issue, it might be 15 or 20 percent, because the bondsman knows if you get deported, you may not make it to court, obviously.  Normally, you pay a bondsman a set fee that you contract with them and they get you out of jail.\r\n\r\n<b>You Only Pay the Bondsman a Percentage of the Total Bail</b>\r\n\r\nLet’s say it’s a $1,000 bond. You’re not going to pay that bondsman $1,000.  You may pay him $200 to get you out of jail, but you only owe the bondsman the money if you didn’t show up for court.  That’s what bonded bail is.\r\n\r\n<strong>When a Misdemeanor Case Is Filed, That Is the Case That Goes to Court</strong>\r\n\r\nThe bail is to ensure you show up for court, and whether you post bail or hire a bondsman, there’s a couple of different ways to get out.  Then the case gets filed.  A misdemeanor case in Texas is filed by information.  That means that there’s an affidavit that accompanies the information, or the complaint, which is signed off on, saying, “We believe this crime was committed,” and then basically it’s filed.  The D.A. stamps his name, and it’s filed.  It’s an actual case that goes to court.\r\n\r\n<b>Felonies Are Indicted, Which Is Decided by a Grand Jury, to Proceed to Court</b>\r\n\r\nA felony case has to be indicted, by a grand jury.  The grand jury typically sits anywhere from 12 to 18 people, and they hear cases.  The grand jury decides is there probable cause to see if this crime was committed?  If the grand jury votes to do a true bill, which means that they’re going to find that the allegations are true, then they’re going to do a true bill of indictment. The case is now filed in the district court for felony.  If a jury finds that there is not probable cause, then the case is no-billed, so no charge is filed.\r\n\r\n<strong>The Grand Jury Views Evidence That Would Otherwise Be Inadmissible in Court</strong>\r\n\r\nThe trick there is the grand jury can look at inadmissible evidence; evidence that should be suppressed, or evidence that would never see the light of day in court.  They can still look at that evidence to determine if a case should be indicted or not.  That’s kind of the trick there, is that they might look at more things than a jury gets to look at.  Just because you get indicted by a grand jury, doesn’t mean you couldn’t win in a jury trial.', 'How Is Bail Set? What Does It Mean to Be Indicted?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'how-is-bail-set-what-does-it-mean-to-be-indicted', '', '', '2014-01-30 10:51:30', '2014-01-30 10:51:30', '', '0', 'http://www.brentbowen.com/?page_id=653', '0', 'page', '', '0');
