INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('655', '1', '2014-01-30 10:40:54', '2014-01-30 10:40:54', '<b>Interviewer: </b>What would be the comparison between someone representing themselves, versus having a public defender, versus having a private attorney?\r\n\r\n<b>A Fool for a Client…</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Brent Bowen: </b>When you represent yourself, there’s the old adage, the person who represents himself has a fool for a client.  If I got in trouble, I’d hire an attorney in a heartbeat.  I wouldn’t try to do it myself.  It’s just not worth it.\r\n\r\nYou need an unbiased perspective to look at the case and take the emotion out of the case.  Obviously, if you’re the one charged with a crime, you’re going to be very emotional about that.  In my opinion, it’s not a good idea to be your own attorney in court.\r\n\r\n<strong>Public Defenders Are Court Appointed and You Do Not Have a Say in Which One Is Representing You</strong>\r\n\r\nIn Denton County, we have a court-appointed wheel, so the way it works is that you are on the list. It’s literally a wheel, and when your name comes up, you get appointed.  Public defenders in the county are set of attorneys.  The problem with public defenders or any court-appointed attorney in the system is there are good ones and there are bad ones.\r\n\r\nIt’s like in any practice; there are good attorneys and bad attorneys.  You’re stuck with whatever attorney the court appoints you.\r\n\r\nYou can always hire an attorney later on, but you can’t pick it.  There’s really good attorneys on the court-appointed system, and there’s really bad attorneys on the court-appointed system.\r\n\r\nI try to treat all my clients the same, whether I’ve been appointed by a court, or if I’m going to do some court-appointed work, or whether it’s a retained client.  I don’t typically differentiate between the two.  Some attorneys do, so the advantage is you get to pick your own attorney.  If you hire an attorney, you’re paying the money to that attorney; you were able to choose that attorney.  That tends to play into it a little bit as well.\r\n\r\n<strong>Private Attorneys Have More Time and Resources to Devote to Each Client</strong>\r\n\r\nObviously, the more resources someone has determines whether you can get a private investigator involved.  You can get a private investigator involved in a court-appointed case, but you’re going to have to show the judge why you need it.  It’s kind of at the judge’s disposal, and the judge’s budget.  They might set the budget, which can limit what resources you can use.\r\n\r\nThere’s ways around it, it’s just obviously more work, which is time, so the bills tend to get high, which makes the judge upset.  You’re going to be responsible for that bill at the end of the day.  Obviously, I prefer to deal with retained clients and I try to keep a lower caseload that way.  I tend to charge sometimes a little bit of a higher fee than some of my competitors, just so I have less cases to focus on, and can focus more time on a client’s case.', 'Self-Representation, Public Defender or a Private Attorney: Which Option Is Best for Your Criminal Case?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'self-representation-public-defender-or-a-private-attorney-which-option-is-best-for-your-criminal-case', '', '', '2014-01-30 10:50:57', '2014-01-30 10:50:57', '', '0', 'http://www.brentbowen.com/?page_id=655', '0', 'page', '', '0');
