INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('657', '1', '2014-01-30 10:42:26', '2014-01-30 10:42:26', '<b>Interviewer: </b>How does someone go about getting their record sealed or expunged?  Is that possible?\r\n\r\n<b>Dismissed Cases Can Be Expunged</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Brent Bowen: </b>It is possible, only in very unique situations.  You have to do one of two things.  Number one, you can only expunge a case if the case has been dismissed, or never filed because the statute of limitations has run, or you’re acquitted.  Those are probably the only reasons why you can get a case expunged, which means all the records are destroyed.\r\n\r\nIf a case gets filed against you, the case gets dismissed and there are no other charges out of that crime, there sometimes is a waiting period depending on the circumstances and you can expunge that crime.\r\n\r\n<b>Charges Entered into a Diversion Program May Be Expunged</b>\r\n\r\nThey also have a first offender program, or pre-trial diversion, and you can expunge pre-trial diversion charges.  The legislature changed that a couple years ago, to expressly make that part of it.   There are very limited circumstances in which you can expunge or destroy your criminal records, or have all the records surrounding it destroyed.\r\n\r\nThat being said, if you know the police investigated you, there’s an argument that you might want to expunge those records after the statute of limitation runs.  Just so the police don’t say, “I remember that guy.  We investigated him a few years ago.”  You want those records disposed of.\r\n\r\n<b>Petition of Nondisclosure</b>\r\n\r\nSealing is not the perfect term to use for adult crimes.  Basically, it’s called petition for nondisclosure.  What a nondisclosure does is it prevents the government and police agencies and governmental agencies from releasing or disclosing the information relating to your arrest and your probation.\r\n\r\n<b>If the Petition Is Granted, You Can Deny the Arrest</b>\r\n\r\nYou can only do petition for nondisclosure on a deferred adjudication.  If you get deferred adjudication, and you meet the requirements, you can have the records sealed or not disclosed at that point in time.  Once the judge grants you a nondisclosure, you can deny the arrest.\r\n\r\nThe bad thing about a nondisclosure is if you’re licensed by the government, or you want to seek a government license to be a hairdresser, or work at a hospital or school there are many different agencies that are exempt from that statute.    If you get deferred and you apply for a job to just a normal business that doesn’t really have any licensing requirements, then it’s going to help you.\r\n\r\n<strong>Certain Government Agencies Will Still Be Able to View the Record, Which May Limit Employment Options</strong>\r\n\r\nIf you want to be an insurance agent or stock broker or a teacher, the nondisclosure’s really not going to help you as much as you think, because they’re still going to see those records.\r\n\r\nYou cannot file a petition of nondisclosure in family violence, injury to a child, or any type of sex offenses, or any time you’ve had a registered sex offender.  Those are all going to be exempt from the nondisclosure statutes, so you can never seal those records.', 'Is It Possible to Have a Case Sealed or Expunged in the Denton County Area?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'is-it-possible-to-have-a-case-sealed-or-expunged-in-the-denton-county-area', '', '', '2014-01-30 10:50:27', '2014-01-30 10:50:27', '', '0', 'http://www.brentbowen.com/?page_id=657', '0', 'page', '', '0');
