r nondisclosure on a deferred adjudication.  If you get deferred adjudication, and you meet the requirements, you can have the records sealed or not disclosed at that point in time.  Once the judge grants you a nondisclosure, you can deny the arrest.\r\n\r\nThe bad thing about a nondisclosure is if you’re licensed by the government, or you want to seek a government license to be a hairdresser, or work at a hospital or school there are many different agencies that are exempt from that statute.    If you get deferred and you apply for a job to just a normal business that doesn’t really have any licensing requirements, then it’s going to help you.\r\n\r\n<strong>Certain Government Agencies Will Still Be Able to View the Record, Which May Limit Employment Options</strong>\r\n\r\nIf you want to be an insurance agent or stock broker or a teacher, the nondisclosure’s really not going to help you as much as you think, because they’re still going to see those records.\r\n\r\nYou cannot file a petition of nondisclosure in family violence, injury to a child, or any type of sex offenses, or any time you’ve had a registered sex offender.  Those are all going to be exempt from the nondisclosure statutes, so you can never seal those records.', 'Is It Possible to Have a Case Sealed or Expunged in the Denton County Area?', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '657-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-01-30 10:42:26', '2014-01-30 10:42:26', '', '657', 'http://www.brentbowen.com/657-revision-v1/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('659', '1', '2014-01-30 10:43:10', '2014-01-30 10:43:10', '<b>Interviewer: </b>Is there anything else about criminal defense that you’d like to add to this?\r\n\r\n<strong>If Your Probation Is in Danger of Being Revoked, Consult with an Attorney as Soon as Possible</strong>\r\n\r\n<b>Brent Bowen: </b>The only thing that we haven’t talked about was probation revocations.  Very often while on probation, people violate some of the conditions.  The probation officer starts talking about, “I’m going to revoke you on probation.”\r\n\r\nThat’s also a perfect time to go talk to an attorney. You can find out what your rights are and what you can and can’t do.  It is very possible that the attorney can negotiate some issues with the probation officer, to keep you from being re-arrested and having your probation revoked.\r\n\r\n<strong>You Also Need an Attorney If Your Probation Has Been Revoked to Minimize Prison or Jail Time</strong>\r\n\r\nEven when it gets revoked, you still want to hire an attorney to help negotiate, and again minimize, your exposure to prison or jail time.  You don’t want to make many admissions to your probation officer.  Again, same thing; the probation officers are there to do what the court tells them to do.  If you admit to, “Did you commit this crime?”  Then they’re going to have to notify the court and the D.A. office that you violated your probation.  Again, it’s important to know what your rights are when you’re dealing with possible probation revocation.  We do handle a large number of those cases.', 'Probation Revocations', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'probation-revocations', '', '', '2014-01-30 10:49:59', '2014-01-30 10:49:59', '', '0', 'http://www.brentbowen.com/?page_id=659', '0', 'page', '', '0');
