INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('735', '1', '2014-02-04 05:05:38', '2014-02-04 05:05:38', '<b>Interviewer: </b> How does somebody go about initiating a divorce? What is the process?\r\n\r\n<b>The Party That Is Initiating the Divorce Files a Petition</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>To start a divorce everyone has to file a petition to divorce. It\'s going to be with or without children, it could be a large estate, a small estate, it can be agreement or not by agreement. Every case actually starts with a petition.\r\n\r\nOnce you file that petition that\'s going to start the legal litigation calendar that you need to run per the law of the state and for Denton County.\r\n\r\n<b>Divorce in the 21st Century: In Current Times, Is It Common That One Party Wants the Divorce and the Other Wants to Continue the Marriage?</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>How does it work when one spouse wants the divorce but the other does not? Are they obligated to get a lawyer? Is that a common occurrence nowadays?\r\n\r\n<b>Once the Petition for Divorce Is Filed, It Can Only Be Revoked by the Petitioner </b>\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>Yes and no. I\'ve had them on both sides of the fence on that one. One part would like to continue the marriage and wants to try, the other party is no longer has a desire to do that. I\'ve had it where both parties just want this over and done with and they are ready to move on with their lives.  That\'s why the petition matters.\r\n\r\nLet\'s say the wife wants a divorce but the husband doesn\'t. The wife files her petition, the husband can\'t come to the court now and say, \"I don\'t want this divorce and you can\'t make me get a divorce.\"\r\n\r\nThe judge is going to tell him, \"The petition is on file, she wants the divorce. It\'s going to happen.\" That\'s why your petition becomes important. Now only because you have a 60 day waiting period before you can finalize anything in a divorce, you need that petition on file. This way, someone can\'t come up and say, \"No, no I\'m done. I don\'t want to do this anymore.\"\r\n\r\nThe only person that can take back a petition, which has been called a non-suit, is the party that filed that petition. They may not want it, but if one party does want it then it\'s going to happen. The divorce will be consummated.', 'The Divorce Process', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'the-divorce-process', '', '', '2014-02-04 11:31:35', '2014-02-04 11:31:35', '', '0', 'http://www.brentbowen.com/?page_id=735', '0', 'page', '', '0');
INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('736', '1', '2014-02-04 05:05:38', '2014-02-04 05:05:38', '<b>Interviewer: </b>Today we\'re going to talk about the big D, divorce. How does somebody go about initiating a divorce? What is the process?\r\n\r\n<b>The Party That Is Initiating the Divorce Files a Petition</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>To start a divorce everyone has to file a petition to divorce. It\'s going to be with or without children, it could be a large estate, a small estate, it can be agreement or not by agreement. Every case actually starts with a petition.\r\n\r\nOnce you file that petition that\'s going to start the legal litigation calendar that you need to run per the law of the state and for Denton County.\r\n\r\n<b>Divorce in the 21st Century: In Current Times, Is It Common That One Party Wants the Divorce and the Other Wants to Continue the Marriage?</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>How does it work when one spouse wants the divorce but the other does not? Are they obligated to get a lawyer? Is that a common occurrence nowadays?\r\n\r\n<b>Once the Petition for Divorce Is Filed, It Can Only Be Revoked by the Petitioner </b>\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>Yes and no. I\'ve had them on both sides of the fence on that one. One part would like to continue the marriage and wants to try, the other party is no longer has a desire to do that. I\'ve had it where both parties just want this over and done with and they are ready to move on with their lives.  That\'s why the petition matters.\r\n\r\nLet\'s say the wife wants a divorce but the husband doesn\'t. The wife files her petition, the husband can\'t come to the court now and say, \"I don\'t want this divorce and you can\'t make me get a divorce.\"\r\n\r\nThe judge is going to tell him, \"The petition is on file, she wants the divorce. It\'s going to happen.\" That\'s why your petition becomes important. Now only because you have a 60 day waiting period before you can finalize anything in a divorce, you need that petition on file. This way, someone can\'t come up and say, \"No, no I\'m done. I don\'t want to do this anymore.\"\r\n\r\nThe only person that can take back a petition, which has been called a non-suit, is the party that filed that petition. They may not want it, but if one party does want it then it\'s going to happen. The divorce will be consummated.', 'The Divorce Process', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '735-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-02-04 05:05:38', '2014-02-04 05:05:38', '', '735', 'http://www.brentbowen.com/735-revision-v1/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('737', '1', '2014-02-04 05:07:06', '2014-02-04 05:07:06', '<b>Interviewer: </b> What does time sharing mean? Who determines the time sharing arrangement?\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b> If you\'re talking about children the time sharing arrangement is going to depend upon certain factors about the parents. Factors include if one party left, if there\'s any mental instability, and if there\'s anything that happened in the home that\'s detrimental to the children.\r\n\r\n<b>Texas Has a Standard Possession Schedule and Allows for an Expanded Schedule to Accommodate Parents Employed in Industries That Do Not Have a Consistent Work Schedule</b>\r\n\r\nIn Texas we have a standard possession schedule. That\'s set out by the legislature.  But some parents may have work schedules that change every six months. As their attorney, you can craft an order that allows deviation from the standard possession schedule.\r\n\r\nThere are different jobs where this is permitted, for example, we may need to change visitation every six months depending upon the work schedule, so the parent can continue to see the children. You can do that with a parent that works as a pilot, as another example and you can do that if the child is under three in Texas.\r\n\r\nThe family bar has gotten together and the county judges and district judges have gotten together and put together a schedule that they like, but there\'s nothing that requires this visitation schedule if the child is under three. If that is the case, you can craft a schedule on your own.\r\n\r\nIf one of the parents wasn\'t married to the other parent and they hadn\'t seen the child for the first year of the child\'s life, they\'ll automatically give them all this time and visitation with the child. You can build into stair step, is what we call it. You progressively get more and more time with your child.\r\n\r\n<b>Example of Time Sharing for Parents of a Five-Year-Old Child</b>\r\n\r\nIn Texas we do have a set schedule for standard possession schedule, which is first, third, and fifth weekends. Depending if it\'s expanded or if it\'s normal we\'ll dictate your start and stop time for that first, third, and fifth weekend. Then you get a day for dinner or an overnight visit during the week depending on that expanded schedule versus the standard one.\r\n\r\nNow on your second and fourth weekends, it\'s not labeled this way, but this is the way it works out. Every week you\'re going to either have a two hour block to have dinner with them on Thursday night or you\'re going to have from after school to on Thursday to Friday morning to return back to school. That\'s going to happen every week. You\'ll get to see your child every week and then you get the additional time on the first, third, and fifth weekends of the month.\r\n\r\nHoliday schedules depend on how you have them written up. Mostly the way that it\'s written in the code is that whoever gets Thanksgiving week is not going to get Christmas. Here in Texas we get about two weeks, so one party gets the first half of the Christmas break, the other party gets the other half of Christmas break. It flip flops every year.\r\n\r\nThe same premise applies for spring break, if you live within a hundred miles of each other. If you live further away, you get more time over the holidays, more time over the summer, and every spring break.\r\n\r\nYou would also have a 30 day block of time, in the summer, that you would get besides those first, third, and fifth and holiday breaks.\r\n\r\n<b>Time Sharing Schedules and the Wishes of the Child</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>Now does that change as the child ages? As the child gets older, he or she is now a 15 year old, and the 15 year old states, \"Oh I don\'t want to hang out with dad this weekend. He\'s not cool.\"\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>No, and that\'s actually a common misconception. It\'s a very difficult thing to try and handle teenage children in divorces. They are more mobile, they have their own cars, they have their own life, and they don\'t really want to have to have a set schedule. By the law, the parent that is in possession of them has an obligation to hand them over to the other parent.\r\n\r\n<b>Teenagers and Time Sharing: If a Child Does Not Go To Visit One Parent, the Other May Face Legal Consequences</b>\r\n\r\nIf that child doesn\'t go, the party that is supposed to turn them over can legally be facing consequences because the child did not see the other parent. Even though they\'re teenagers, in Texas you\'re an adult at 17, but under the family code you don\'t fall out of the family code until you\'re either out of high school or 18, which event comes later.\r\n\r\nI find this issue is a huge misconception. A lot of parents are able to work together, but some aren\'t. You are responsible for your teenage child not showing up to a visitation. That is a rule across the board for standard visitations.\r\n\r\nThat\'s what the legislature came up with, believing that arrangement would be best in the best interest of the children as far as time away from and with their parent. That\'s the schedule that they came up with. This arrangement is the one that is primarily used, unless you have other circumstances or you make an agreement otherwise. The teenager would be required to go if the receiving parent wanted them to be there.', 'Child Custody Is Now Referred to as Time Sharing', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'child-custody-is-now-referred-to-as-time-sharing', '', '', '2014-02-04 05:17:53', '2014-02-04 05:17:53', '', '0', 'http://www.brentbowen.com/?page_id=737', '0', 'page', '', '0');
