INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('739', '1', '2014-02-04 05:07:48', '2014-02-04 05:07:48', '<b>Interviewer: </b> Do you see equal time sharing happening in Texas in the near future?\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>Yes actually I do. Surprisingly a lot of parents are able, with children, to come up with a schedule that works for the kids. I have to say, and I hope that I\'m not misspeaking; I\'ve noticed this primarily in the last year. It hasn\'t been this way prior to that.\r\n\r\n<b>Recently, Equal Time Sharing Seems to Be a Growing Trend among Families</b>\r\n\r\nThe parents have been more flexible with their ability to make adjustments to the schedule so they both have time with the children. Both parents have greater access to them and they are both able to participate in other activities to make up for time that they\'re missing by not having them all the time.\r\n\r\nI know some of the other attorneys are talking the same way. I don\'t know that that\'s the predominate arrangement across the state or anything like that or if that\'s going to be the new paradigm. I have noticed in my cases, there is more of a shift towards parents wanting to work that schedule out versus having that standard visitation.\r\n\r\n<b>Specialized Visitations Can Work If Both Parents Agree; Otherwise, They Have to Follow the Standard Visitation Schedule</b>\r\n\r\nStandard visitation can always be your fall back.  If the parties agree, they can agree to whatever they want as long as it\'s an agreement. If they can\'t agree, then they follow the standard visitation schedule.\r\n\r\nI always think it\'s better to try and work the schedule to accommodate the children first, of course at a certain age and their schedules. Then the parents schedules, both working at this point in this economy, some people have had to take jobs that they normally wouldn\'t have taken. They have hours that they normally wouldn\'t have that are really conducive to a flexible visitation schedule; such as the police officers.\r\n\r\nThe legislature hasn\'t changed anything as far as visitation goes. The presumption and minimums are still set out for the standard visitation. I have noticed that I\'ve had more requests for that specialized visitation, which is what we would call it, in the last nine months.\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>Do you think this is due to the fact that there are a more working mothers and stay-at-home dads than before?\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>Yes, and that\'s true I have them on both sides. I have clients where the dad has been the one that has stayed at home with the children, the mom has been the primary bread winner. They still want to share the children as much as possible, and that might be some of it too.\r\n\r\nThe economy has been a big factor; many people changed jobs and changed locations. The question is how can you make that work? It needs to work so the children’s needs are still being met.\r\n\r\nIt\'s hard to be a single parent, no matter which side you\'re on; if you have help or you don\'t have help. It\'s hard to get the children to their practices and make sure they\'re eating and doing their schoolwork. Hopefully that continues. I like schedules we can work out like that.', 'Will the Courts in Texas begin Instituting Equal Time Sharing? ', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'will-the-courts-in-texas-begin-instituting-equal-time-sharing', '', '', '2014-02-04 05:17:19', '2014-02-04 05:17:19', '', '0', 'http://www.brentbowen.com/?page_id=739', '0', 'page', '', '0');
