INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('741', '1', '2014-02-04 05:08:57', '2014-02-04 05:08:57', '<b>Interviewer: </b>What is alimony and how is the amount determined?\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>We still have spousal maintenance, not necessarily alimony here. Texas law has just changed last year.\r\n\r\n<b>Texas Law Recently Enacted New Criteria for Spousal Maintenance</b>\r\n\r\nThis was a huge change for us. We had spousal maintenance and you had to meet some pretty strict requirements. Our law has changed and the legislature created these stair steps, essentially, depending upon length of marriage. There are still criteria to meet in order to qualify.\r\n\r\nThe length of marriage is one of the factors that would determine how long you would have spousal maintenance and up to how much you receive. That\'s something new for us in the last year. Essentially spousal maintenance was only for a full-time stay-at-home mom that needed to go back and get some education in order to support herself for the children.\r\n\r\nYou had to have certain requirements, or family violence had to be part of the divorce. Those are still factors but not a requirement like they used to be. Previously, you couldn\'t get spousal maintenance unless those factors were present. Spousal maintenance in Texas is not yet a popular issue.\r\n\r\n<b>How Is Spousal Maintenance Determined?</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>It seems like you are seeing some improvement on that end, but at the same time how exactly is it determined and how does it work now?\r\n\r\n<b>Spousal Maintenance Is Determined by Length of Marriage in Texas</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>It depends on the length of marriage, such as if you\'ve been married for 10 years or 20 years or 25 to 30 years. If you were married for 30 years you get seven years of spousal maintenance. The other party is going to be making payments to you for that time period. It\'s going to be up to 20% of their income.\r\n\r\nIt\'s going to be your spousal maintenance payments. It’s a mathematical equation depending upon the years of marriage and ability to earn and what the other party is earning. Then you still have the list of qualifying factors.\r\n\r\nIn my situation, you have two attorneys, and we make essentially the same salary. If we were to divorce then I wouldn\'t have a financial need from him. I would qualify for maintenance but I don\'t have a financial need to have that extra assistance.\r\n\r\nThrough our estate and through my own earning ability I should be able to meet my minimum needs. That\'s what the spousal maintenance laws are here. If you\'re located in another state, it doesn\'t have anything to do with that. If you\'ve been married, you are awarded alimony most times. In Texas, we are newly coming around to this concept. I know there\'s a lot of attorneys, especially from attorneys here in [inaudible 00:33:34] for detained in a spousal maintenance laws to go in affect for us, because we just didn\'t have what you would call alimony.\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>Now will it always be 20%?\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>No that\'s why I want to keep from quoting right off the top of my head because I always want to double check before I say something that [inaudible 00:34:13]. I\'m just saying in general, that\'s the general concept of how spousal maintenance works here in Texas.\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>Let\'s say I was a successful business man and I was married to a woman who probably didn\'t have that many work skills, but we got married none the less; we\'re going through a divorce now. Then I would have to probably provide her with a certain amount of my income is there\'s a divorce?\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>Yes, that\'s correct. The length of time that you would have to do that is going to depend upon how long you were married.\r\n\r\n<b>Spousal Maintenance and Child Support Are Viewed as Completely Different; a Spouse Receiving Maintenance Is Not Required to Use the Funds for Care of the Children</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b> Now child support is totally different from spousal maintenance, is that right?\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>Yes, child support is completely different from spousal maintenance.\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>Does that spousal support cover child care costs or anything that had to do with care for the child?\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>No, spousal support is a completely a separate component of a divorce than child support. Child support deals along only with the children and their needs and the paying parent\'s income.', 'In Texas, Alimony Is Known as Spousal Maintenance', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'in-texas-alimony-is-known-as-spousal-maintenance', '', '', '2014-02-04 05:16:44', '2014-02-04 05:16:44', '', '0', 'http://www.brentbowen.com/?page_id=741', '0', 'page', '', '0');
