INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('743', '1', '2014-02-04 05:09:56', '2014-02-04 05:09:56', '<b>Interviewer: </b> Let\'s talk about equitable distribution of assets and debts.\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>When you\'re talking about an equitable distribution, what you\'re saying to someone is here are all of your assets, here are all of your debts and we\'re going to try and make it as close to 50/50 as possible between dividing up your debt and dividing up your assets. An asset is something that\'s worth money.\r\n\r\nThere are benefits in having an attorney handle this matter but no one is saying you can\'t do that on your own.  The attorneys do the valuations of the assets and then when we start talking about division.\r\n\r\n<b>Many Couples Dispute the Equitable Division</b>\r\n\r\nMost people don\'t believe 50% of their marital estate is equitable. They don\'t want to take the debt or they want all the assets. That\'s generally how a divorce is. One party wants to take all the assets and give the person all the debt.\r\n\r\nIn Texas, you hear the 50/50 all the time, that\'s where the starting point is—at 50%. Then from there, depending upon things that have happened in the marriage that one other party has done to the other party or even to the property. If you get into, there\'s been a benefit into the marital estate. You start working from that 50% to go to your 55% or 60% on one side versus 40% on the other side.\r\n\r\nEvery case is pretty much individualized because every person has their own assets. Your larger estates includes ones that own businesses and own property. When you start with property that goes over state lines or trust funds, those are going to be where your distributions become really important. That is where the parties are going to be fighting the hardest versus the child issue and the divorce.\r\n\r\n<b>Do Both Parties’ Attorneys Work Together on Equitable Distribution? </b>\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>Do attorneys work with other attorneys and try to negotiate from there?\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>I\'ve had the situation go both ways. One way is where the parties have sat down and looked at their, what we essentially call an inventory, of what they have accumulated both in debt and assets. They come in and say, \"We’ve sat down together and we\'ve decided she wants these items, I want these. Let\'s write it up.\" I\'ve had it that way and then I\'ve had it where it\'s highly contiguous. Your client or the other client wants all of the assets and they want to give all the debt to the other party.\r\n\r\nIt is the responsibility of the attorney to get them divorced and separated and split up their estate where the assets are distributed in a somewhat equal manner. The attorney will try to gain assets that that particular person wants over the assets that they don\'t want.\r\n\r\n<b>Mediation Can Be an Option to have Couples Agree on Asset and Debt Distribution            </b>\r\n\r\nWho wants this debt, who wants that debt? That\'s what mediation is for, also to get you there versus having to prove it all to the court. Oftentimes that\'s just what we do, helping our clients get to that point where they can start working together. Not only are things changing, to this is how we\'re going to have to do it when you look at numbers and property and debts and who is responsible for this and who should be responsible for this.\r\n\r\nThe law it allows you to get to this and this is why ... and retirement accounts and what are the retirement laws and [inaudible 00:40:33] that restrict you from taking money or transferring money.\r\n\r\nAll of that comes into play in a divorce when you\'re talking about property. It\'s not just a, \"I have a house.\" Equitable division has to encompass everything from debt to retirement accounts, cars to boats.\r\n\r\nThe attorneys really do, for the most part, try to work it out. We try and do a little give and take. That\'s where mediation is really valuable. In the Denton County mediation, we have a special mediation program that many other counties don\'t have that offers reduced mediation.\r\n\r\n<b>Mediation Promotes Collaboration and Leaves the Decision Making to the Parties as Opposed to the Judges </b>\r\n\r\nYou push people towards that collaborative law situation. We try and work it out and get the decision making out of the judicial system. When you go to court, you\'ve got a few hours to present all of this information.\r\n\r\n<b>Businesses Are a Difficult Asset to Divide between Divorcing Couples</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>What would you say is one of the more difficult assets to give up?\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>I would say businesses. Married couples that have created a business together have a hard time dividing it. Difficulties arise if one party has interest in the business, whether it is with other partners or a law firm or a medical clinic. A law firm you can\'t own a share in if you\'re not an attorney.\r\n\r\nThe problem becomes, how do value that? How do you value the property that\'s in the business? Who own what portion? If you\'re not listed as business partners it is very difficult to get to the bottom of that. That\'s where you get into what types of money payouts are fair, what are you going to do with this business, how is it going to continue on? Who\'s going to own it? How are you going to proceed forward, how is money going to be divided, does this count for the divorce, does it count for future payment?\r\n\r\nThe business divisions are the most difficult things to divide, I would say. You have to devise more intricate plans. Tax consequences can also be a big issue.', 'What Is Equitable Distribution of Assets and Debts?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'what-is-equitable-distribution-of-assets-and-debts', '', '', '2014-02-04 05:16:05', '2014-02-04 05:16:05', '', '0', 'http://www.brentbowen.com/?page_id=743', '0', 'page', '', '0');
INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('744', '1', '2014-02-04 05:09:56', '2014-02-04 05:09:56', '<b>Interviewer: </b> Let\'s talk about equitable distribution of assets and debts.\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>When you\'re talking about an equitable distribution, what you\'re saying to someone is here are all of your assets, here are all of your debts and we\'re going to try and make it as close to 50/50 as possible between dividing up your debt and dividing up your assets. An asset is something that\'s worth money.\r\n\r\nThere are benefits in having an attorney handle this matter but no one is saying you can\'t do that on your own.  The attorneys do the valuations of the assets and then when we start talking about division.\r\n\r\n<b>Many Couples Dispute the Equitable Division</b>\r\n\r\nMost people don\'t believe 50% of their marital estate is equitable. They don\'t want to take the debt or they want all the assets. That\'s generally how a divorce is. One party wants to take all the assets and give the person all the debt.\r\n\r\nIn Texas, you hear the 50/50 all the time, that\'s where the starting point is—at 50%. Then from there, depending upon things that have happened in the marriage that one other party has done to the other party or even to the property. If you get into, there\'s been a benefit into the marital estate. You start working from that 50% to go to your 55% or 60% on one side versus 40% on the other side.\r\n\r\nEvery case is pretty much individualized because every person has their own assets. Your larger estates includes ones that own businesses and own property. When you start with property that goes over state lines or trust funds, those are going to be where your distributions become really important. That is where the parties are going to be fighting the hardest versus the child issue and the divorce.\r\n\r\n<b>Do Both Parties’ Attorneys Work Together on Equitable Distribution? </b>\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>Do attorneys work with other attorneys and try to negotiate from there?\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>I\'ve had the situation go both ways. One way is where the parties have sat down and looked at their, what we essentially call an inventory, of what they have accumulated both in debt and assets. They come in and say, \"We’ve sat down together and we\'ve decided she wants these items, I want these. Let\'s write it up.\" I\'ve had it that way and then I\'ve had it where it\'s highly contiguous. Your client or the other client wants all of the assets and they want to give all the debt to the other party.\r\n\r\nIt is the responsibility of the attorney to get them divorced and separated and split up their estate where the assets are distributed in a somewhat equal manner. The attorney will try to gain assets that that particular person wants over the assets that they don\'t want.\r\n\r\n<b>Mediation Can Be an Option to have Couples Agree on Asset and Debt Distribution            </b>\r\n\r\nWho wants this debt, who wants that debt? That\'s what mediation is for, also to get you there versus having to prove it all to the court. Oftentimes that\'s just what we do, helping our clients get to that point where they can start working together. Not only are things changing, to this is how we\'re going to have to do it when you look at numbers and property and debts and who is responsible for this and who should be responsible for this.\r\n\r\nThe law it allows you to get to this and this is why ... and retirement accounts and what are the retirement laws and [inaudible 00:40:33] that restrict you from taking money or transferring money.\r\n\r\nAll of that comes into play in a divorce when you\'re talking about property. It\'s not just a, \"I have a house.\" Equitable division has to encompass everything from debt to retirement accounts, cars to boats.\r\n\r\nThe attorneys really do, for the most part, try to work it out. We try and do a little give and take. That\'s where mediation is really valuable. In the Denton County mediation, we have a special mediation program that many other counties don\'t have that offers reduced mediation.\r\n\r\n<b>Mediation Promotes Collaboration and Leaves the Decision Making to the Parties as Opposed to the Judges </b>\r\n\r\nYou push people towards that collaborative law situation. We try and work it out and get the decision making out of the judicial system. When you go to court, you\'ve got a few hours to present all of this information.\r\n\r\n<b>Businesses Are a Difficult Asset to Divide between Divorcing Couples</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>What would you say is one of the more difficult assets to give up?\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>I would say businesses. Married couples that have created a business together have a hard time dividing it. Difficulties arise if one party has interest in the business, whether it is with other partners or a law firm or a medical clinic. A law firm you can\'t own a share in if you\'re not an attorney.\r\n\r\nThe problem becomes, how do value that? How do you value the property that\'s in the business? Who own what portion? If you\'re not listed as business partners it is very difficult to get to the bottom of that. That\'s where you get into what types of money payouts are fair, what are you going to do with this business, how is it going to continue on? Who\'s going to own it? How are you going to proceed forward, how is money going to be divided, does this count for the divorce, does it count for future payment?\r\n\r\nThe business divisions are the most difficult things to divide, I would say. You have to devise more intricate plans. Tax consequences can also be a big issue.', 'What Is Equitable Distribution of Assets and Debts?', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '743-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-02-04 05:09:56', '2014-02-04 05:09:56', '', '743', 'http://www.brentbowen.com/743-revision-v1/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('745', '1', '2014-02-04 05:11:07', '2014-02-04 05:11:07', '<b>Interviewer: </b>Do the same 50/50 rules apply for couples that were only married a short amount of time?\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b> You\'re saying that a party has only been married for four months, and they bought a house during that four months, but husband owned a house prior and has cars that he bought prior that are paid off. They bought a car while they were married in those four months. He\'s been working for the same company for 20 years, but they\'ve only been married for four months.\r\n\r\n<b>In a Short Term Marriage, There Are Distinctions between Marital Property and Separate Property</b>\r\n\r\nIn that situation it would be the community property versus the separate property. This is a factor when it\'s a shorter term marriage. People may not understand that they don\'t qualify to get to the separate property and that\'s where you want to make your determination.\r\n\r\nThis is a situation where our job becomes difficult. Were all these items brought in or owned prior to the marriage, so it\'s not considered in the marriage? We want to keep it that way, and you can\'t get to it or count it. All you can count is from the date of marriage, and anything that happened after that.\r\n\r\nIn the example I just provided, that would be the house that they bought together and the car. Then the four months that they were married, his retirement of his 20 years job. She\'ll be entitled to the portion of money that was put in during the four months while they were married.\r\n\r\nIn Texas we have, you have the ability to distinguish between the two entities; it\'s just distinguishing them and making sure that they\'re not being accounted if they should be. Then we also have crossover to where you can change separate property into community property and it becomes part of the distribution.\r\n\r\n<b>Prenuptial and Postnuptial Agreements</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>Is that common at all or is that generally a rare thing that happens?\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>No, actually it is common. A lot of people don\'t understand and that is where prenuptial and postnuptial property agreements come into play. I know it seems like that\'s just something you see in the movies but I have done them. Especially in cases, like I stated, where you\'ve got a lot of family money and a family business and you want to protect it.\r\n\r\nA postnuptial and a prenuptial is always a really good idea. Then it protects your interest and you know that is set and it will not be transferred into community property. It\'s going to always be separate property.\r\n\r\n<b>A Prenuptial or Postnuptial Protects Separate Property from Being Transferred into Community Property</b>\r\n\r\nMost people don\'t want to start out that way, because it seems as if you\'re planning for a divorce. It does make sure that your estate stays separate. You can easily convert, where most people don\'t understand that aspect. You can easily convert something that is considered separate property in Texas into community property. An example could be an inheritance. It always starts out as separate, but depending on how you dispose of it—it can become community property.\r\n\r\n<b>What Are the Differences between a Prenuptial and a Postnuptial Agreement?</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>With a prenup and postnup—what are the differences between those two contracts?\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>Essentially the prenuptial is the agreement that you write that contains generalities. You disclose your property and you agree where things are going to go. There are certain things federally that you can\'t divide prior to getting married. You can have a prenuptial agreement that says this is what we\'re doing, but because of certain laws, you can\'t consummate it as a type of property to give away or a right to give away until after the consummation of the marriage, which would be your marriage certificate.\r\n\r\nOnce that\'s signed, that\'s where your postnuptial comes in. It\'s a property agreement after marriage. You\'re agreeing that this is how you\'re going to separate your property. You\'re just following up that pre-marital agreement that you\'re saying, like [inaudible 00:48:39] Laws, tax laws, and retirement stuff. You can\'t give those rights away or determine those rights in prenuptial agreements.\r\n\r\nThat\'s where your post property agreements come in. They can also protect assets if an event occurs that you didn\'t foresee or you acquire property that you want named in a different manner. A couple may have all of this property that they intend to keep separate. But they have decided together that they are going to but this one piece of property and they want it to be community property. You can then create a post-agreement that stipulates this property is going to be considered under the community property per our prenuptial agreement.\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>If someone wanted, before they were to get married, could they go to an attorney and inquire about a prenuptial agreement?\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>We\'ve done them in our office before. They\'re not as predominant in family law. They\'re more common in second marriages. I\'ve had clients that have come to protect their assets the second time around. Prenuptials are drafted more frequently for second marriages than in first marriages.\r\n\r\nAlthough, again, if it\'s family money and family businesses that are trying to be protected; I\'ve done those where they\'re trying to protect the family and they can\'t ever come in and get that. The other party couldn\'t come in and get that. Not necessarily the person that\'s getting married thinking about that, but the older family members that want their business to stay there.\r\n\r\n<b>Can You Stipulate That Property Only Passes to a Child Instead of the Spouse?</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>Could they designate perhaps or have a clause that stipulates certain property would only go to a child?\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>Depending on how it\'s owned, with that example you\'re getting into estate planning at that point. You would have to create a trust and what properties should be included in that and how you want it divided or owned.\r\n\r\nYou can do that, except for you\'re looking at more how is this piece of property going to be owned, how is it going to be titled, how is it going to be deeded to someone else? Is that going to be covered through a trust estate planning? It\'s not really in the family code realm to do that.\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>What if there is a dispute among the family and then the wife feels entitled to some property that the children though they were inheriting?\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>We have homestead laws underneath the [inaudible 00:52:05] code. Being married gives you certain rights and certain situations where you can contest property left to the children, for example. A second marriage where the children are older, the married parties are older, and one is sickly and passes on and the family thought that it was all separate but it has been converted to community. Now the situation is the wife versus the family. The only designation you can bestow is if you\'re talking about just labeling what a piece of property is, not who it can go to.\r\n\r\n<b>In Texas, Non-Marital Property Is Referred to as Separate Property</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>Is this referred to as marital property versus non-marital property or real property?\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>It\'s actually, in Texas, it is separate property versus community property. Community is what you\'ve bought during the marriage that\'s owned by the both of you. Separate property would be something that you owned prior to the marriage and wasn\'t purchased by money that was made during the marital lifetime.\r\n\r\n<b>Divorces Are Complicated Issues When the Parties Need to Agree on Both Time Sharing and Property and Debt Division</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Interviewer: </b>Is there anything else that you\'d like to add or something that I may not have covered?\r\n\r\n<b>Chrysandra Bowen: </b>I think that there are two sides to a divorce that come into play as you\'re trying to divide up property and money and debts. Then you\'re also trying to deal with children. In some instances, divorces are more complicated because of that and you, as the attorney, have a wide-range of focus on the case. It\'s not focused on just children and it\'s not focused on just property. It\'s focusing on the both if you have children in a divorce cases.\r\n\r\nSometimes you can settle one side of it, but you can\'t settle out the other side and that might cause the matter to become protracted. Divorces generally take more time and are more inclusive. The parties are contentious when they don\'t agree on anything. You can have it where you completely agree on the children, but you can\'t agree on any of the money or property or debt or vice versa.', 'Is Equitable Distribution Different in a Short Term Marriage?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'is-equitable-distribution-different-in-a-short-term-marriage', '', '', '2014-02-04 05:15:29', '2014-02-04 05:15:29', '', '0', 'http://www.brentbowen.com/?page_id=745', '0', 'page', '', '0');
